<HEAD>States Denied Chance To Tax Income From Federal Securities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Less than two weeks after creating a potential new source of federal tax money, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> is denying a similar opportunity for state treasuries. The justices on Monday refused to let states tax pension fund income from investments in federal government securities. On April 20, the court had ruled that the federal government may tax the interest earned on state and municipal bonds. Although congressional leaders say there is no plan to impose such taxes, the court's ruling last month cleared away a constitutional hurdle in the event <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> some day changes federal tax law. Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, writing for the court on April 20, said giving the federal government power to tax state and municipal bonds does not suggest that states should have reciprocal power. `` States can never tax the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> directly,'' he said. `` The federal tax immunity has always been greater than the states' immunity. That opinion was reinforced indirectly Monday as the court rejected an appeal by <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> officials seeking to tax income from such federal obligations as treasury bills and short-term borrowing. <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> officials said they should be allowed to tax the income after it is distributed to retirees. The <ORGANIZATION> Vermont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last December upheld a ruling by a state judge who said the pension fund money is tax-exempt. Superior Court Judge <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Katz </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Windsor </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> ruled that interest on federal obligations is immune from state taxation even when the income is passed on by a pension fund to a retired investor. `` In practical operation, the tax in question was in fact a state tax on interest derived from federal obligations,'' <PERSON> Katz </PERSON> said. The fact that pension money was passed on to someone other than the fund itself does not eliminate the exemption enjoyed by investments in federal securities, he said. The judge rejected arguments by state officials that interest on a government security is exempt `` only in the hands of the original recipient unless there is a specific federal statute to pass through the tax-exempt character of such income.'' <PERSON> Katz </PERSON> ruled in favor of <PERSON> Loren </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Keys </PERSON>, who when he retired in 1981 received a lump-sum distribution of $ 141,000 from a savings plan in which he had invested. The money included $ 35,000 in interest on federal securities. <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> officials said Keys owed an additional tax of $ 1,246 on the income from the government obligations. The court rulings in Keys' favor meant he received a tax refund of $ 203 plus interest. <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> officials said a lot more was at stake. They said the state court rulings could force them to examine the source of payments from pension and mutual funds, corporate dividends and even bank deposit interest and then eliminate from the state's tax base any income traced to investments in federal obligations.
</TEXT>
