<HEAD>Ohio Has A Home-State Presidential Ballot In Some Districts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Traficant </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> congressman waging an on-again, off-again campaign for president, is hoping to pick up a few delegates today in his home state but admits his chances of winning even his own congressional district are slim. <PERSON> Traficant </PERSON>, a Democrat from suburban <LOCATION> Youngstown </LOCATION> who also is seeking his third term in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, announced last summer that he would run for president to attract attention to the problems of his congressional district, which has been hard hit by the decline of the steel industry. <PERSON> Traficant </PERSON> said he would run a national campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination, but it never materialized. He blamed a lack of money. `` If I had the same amount of money these other candidates had in the state of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and could have come on TV the past two weeks, there would have been a fight,'' he said. <PERSON> Leesa </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> secretary of state's office said <PERSON> Traficant </PERSON> met the qualifications to get onto the ballot in 12 of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>'s 21 congressional districts. A former sheriff, <PERSON> Traficant </PERSON> is best known for successfully defending himself against charges that he accepted $ 163,000 from mobsters in 1980. But he had little name recognition outside his own district. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Binning </PERSON>, chairman of the political science department at <ORGANIZATION> Youngstown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Traficant </PERSON>'s presidential candidacy was actually given some credence early on because so many of the Democratic candidates were not well known nationally. But ultimately, <PERSON> Binning </PERSON> said, `` I think <PERSON> Traficant </PERSON> would have to win a major statewide office in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> in order to be considered a viable candidate for president.'' A survey conducted by <ORGANIZATION> Youngstown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> suggested residents of his district favor <PERSON> Traficant </PERSON> as a congressman, but not as a presidential candidate. The poll, commissioned by The <ORGANIZATION> Youngstown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vindicator </ORGANIZATION>, indicated 38 percent of the 697 people surveyed favor <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the Democratic front-runner, with <PERSON> Traficant </PERSON> supported by 14 percent and <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> backed by 11 percent. Nearly a quarter of the participants were undecided. However, more than 70 percent of the same respondents supported <PERSON> Traficant </PERSON>'s bid to a third term in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The poll was conducted between April 11 and April 20 and had a margin of error of 5-6 percentage points.
