<HEAD>Meese Critics Include Graffiti Artists</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX22 of May 2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> is the apparent target of anonymous graffiti artists who have left inscriptions such as `` sleazy'' and `` resign'' on the walls of the main <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> building. The graffiti began appearing at about the time two top aides to <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> resigned March 29 due to concern about problems associated with the criminal investigation of <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>. The word `` sleazy'' last week was scrawled in black, 4-inch-high letters on a second-floor staircase in the middle of the building. The stairwell is far from <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s fifth-floor office but is heavily traveled. Employees first noticed the graffiti there Friday, said a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyer who spoke on condition of anonymity. The basement and first-floor levels of the staircase are heavily traveled because they lead to the cafeteria. In another instance, the word `` resign'' was scribbled on a wall near <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s office but it was cleaned off quickly, said department sources, speaking on condition of anonymity. Such graffiti started appearing around the same time that Deputy Attorney General <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> and criminal division chief <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Weld </PERSON> submitted their protest resignations March 29, the course said. <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> and <PERSON> Weld </PERSON> quit out of concern that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s continued tenure as attorney general was hurting the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s operation, morale and public image, sources said. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> on Monday for a meeting of police executives. Independent counsel <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> last May 11 launched an investigation of <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s activities including his involvement with the scandal-plagued <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a $ 1 billion Iraqi oil pipeline. The probe also has examined his holdings of regional <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> telephone stock and his wife's $ 40,000-a-year job. The money for <PERSON> Ursula </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s job comes from a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> family whose real estate company leases office space to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>.
