<HEAD>Bush Backers May Make Dukakis' Budget-Balancing Struggle A
Campaign Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who has made his efficiency as a manager one of the key selling points in his presidential campaign, is struggling to balance his state budgets for this year and next year. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' budget-balancing efforts are turning into something of a balancing act, because his status as the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> front-runner puts him under intense scrutiny. Supporters of Republican rival <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> are hoping the situation will provide them with ammunition they can use against the governor. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> boasts that he has given <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> nine balanced budgets as governor, including the current one for fiscal 1988, and that he will do the same for the coming fiscal year. But he'll have to find some way to make up a $ 77 million revenue shortfall this year, and already has proposed $ 233 million in additional cuts to offset supplementary spending. `` We will make the necessary adjustments which will make it possible for us to live within our income,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said last week. He said there are `` a number of ways to do that,'' but has n't said exactly which way he favors <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> backers were rubbing their hands in anticipation. `` I think it raises a credibility issue for the governor,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Cellucci </PERSON>, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s state campaign chairman. `` He has talked about balancing a federal budget, yet it appears he is going to have difficulty with a fiscal 1989 state budget.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said he will work matters out with the legislature. But some lawmakers are grumbling that that has n't happened yet. `` You are telling us you are going to work with us, and you have n't worked with us,'' Rep. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodgkins </PERSON>, a Democrat on the budget-writing <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, told <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' budget chief, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Keefe </PERSON>, during an appearance before the committee last week No one doubts that the budgets ultimately will be balanced, because they must be under the state constitution. But how <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> does it could become a campaign issue. `` He is either going to have to raise taxes or cut human services spending, neither of which he wants to do. So it's something we -LRB- Republicans -RRB- are obviously going to watch very carefully,'' said <PERSON> Cellucci </PERSON> Advocacy groups fighting to keep funding for their programs are mindful of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' status as a presidential candidate. `` I think the governor running for president has created a situation where the advocates feel that they can leverage his cooperation more _ that they can make him look bad if they do n't get what they want,'' said <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Salisbury </PERSON>, the state budget director <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and his aides have consistently said he will not cut existing services to balance this year's budget, but will instead clamp down on program expansions, primarily in human services. But even that tactic is bringing complaints. `` People were promised ... they were going to get this service and they still have n't gotten it yet,'' said <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION>. `` That is suffering and you ca n't take that away.'' The <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> administration had projected 6.6 percent revenue growth, but this week reduced its estimate to 5.7 percent. Even so, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Voke </PERSON> says the administration's revenue estimates are too optimistic. A large part of the shortfall is blamed on smaller-than-expected corporate tax collections due to a state law allowing state companies to use losses on out-of-state subsidiaries to reduce their <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> tax bill. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has proposed changing this measure. Meanwhile, the state has an appeal pending with the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. The governor has proposed a $ 700 million package of savings and revenue increases to balance his fiscal 1989 budget. Some of the controversial features include: _ Recouping $ 70 million in unclaimed bottle deposits from beverage wholesalers That issue is also before the courts. _ Spending $ 22 million for more tax collectors _ some of the nearly 1,600 new jobs contained in the budget _ to raise $ 190 million in new revenue _ Raising $ 55 million by requiring applicants for Medicaid nursing home coverage to agree to a state lien on their homes for reimbursement after they die The administration has modified the proposal to say Medicaid eligibility will be delayed after applicants transfer assets to others, depending on the size of the transfers.
