<HEAD>View From The Provinces: It Doesn't Really Matter Who Wins</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FOIX, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The political joustings, coded language and sophistictated election arguments of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> fade long before they reach this French provincial capital. To the residents of <LOCATION> Foix </LOCATION>, President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> and challenger <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> are just about the same. `` Do you know what ` bof' means?'' asks 80-year-old <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Boy </PERSON>, a retired draftsman, as he sipped his morning coffee on the main square of this lovely town nestled in the foothills of the Pyrenees. <PERSON> Bof </PERSON> is a French expression that amounts to a verbal shrug. And that's exactly how Boy and many other inhabitants of <LOCATION> Foix </LOCATION> view Sunday's election runoff between the Socialist president and the conservative premier. `` Whether its one or the other, things will continue just the same,'' said Boy. `` It's ` le bof' in general. <LOCATION> Foix </LOCATION>, a town of about 10,000 residents 500 miles from <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, is the capital of the <ORGANIZATION> Ariege </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, one of the least populated districts of the country. It is dominated by the 11th century chateau of the Counts of <LOCATION> Foix </LOCATION> perched on a massive rock overlooking the town. The area has a long Socialist tradition, and because of this <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> is favored, but with more resignation than enthusiasm. On April 24, in the first round of voting, the Ariege gave <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> 41 percent of its vote, seven points above the president's national score, and 18 percent to <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, two points under his overall showing. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> no doubt will win again here Sunday, but it will be a gut vote more than a carefully reasoned choice. <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Doumenc </PERSON>, who for the past 25 years has been the local correspondent for the <LOCATION> Toulouse </LOCATION> newspaper 50 miles away, put it best when he said the things people here really care about are television reception and a proposed tunnel to <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. `` Mitterrand does n't have a program for after May 8,'' said <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> <PERSON> Firon </PERSON>, a local homebuilder. `` Really, there is no fundamental difference between the two. And they both need the <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> vote.'' <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>, leader of the extreme right <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, won 14.4 percent in the first round, stunning many political observers. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> campaigned hard on a platform of ridding <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> of its immigrants and cracking down on law and order. In the Ariege, despite its leftist tradition, <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> won 10.3 percent. It's hard to find somebody who will own up to voting for the extreme right and many Fuxiens, as local residents are called, were looking suspiciously at their neighbors last week. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rouch </PERSON> lounged on a bench in <LOCATION> Foix </LOCATION>'s packed criminal court, wearing the traditional black bailiff's robe. A crowd waited for the jury to return its verdict in a sensational local murder case. `` The Ariege is a place where we live well,'' he said. `` There is no pollution, no racism. There is unemployment, yes ... but we live well. I do n't know about <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>. It's a rejection phenomenon.'' Despite the lack of enthusiasm for <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, polls after the first round show him winning the runoff by scores ranging from 53-47 percent to 57-43 percent. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> `` still represents a popular image that no other political group can match,'' said defense attorney <PERSON> Yves </PERSON> <PERSON> Saez </PERSON>, just before the jury convicted his client and sentenced her to 12 years in prison for bludgeoning her husband to death. In the Cafe de la Mairie on the night of the great debate between <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, most of the clientele sat in the back room drinking and socializing. Up front, where the debate was on the television, only a few folks paid attention. Lined up on a bench were four working-class men in their 30s and 40s, stonefaced, arms crossed. After the two-hour debate, they got up as a unit and left. One of them, in another typical French mannerism, expressed his opinion by filling his cheeks with air and letting it out with a soft puff. `` They're all the same.'' The next morning at the farmers' market, a peasant selling her cheese declared herself for <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, but was hard put to explain why. `` We live on agricultural subsidies,'' she said. `` For peasants it's an absolute necessity.'' Has <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> threatened to cut subsidies? `` Well, you have the feeling that you are listened to under the left. Under the right, decisions are made without consultation, and that's it.''
