<HEAD>Reagan Aides Recommend Veto of Benefits for `Atomic Veterans'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s advisers are recommending that he veto a bill which would grant some new benefits to `` atomic veterans,'' the American servicemen exposed to radiation in the 1945 occupation of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> or during post-World War II tests of nuclear weapons. The bill was sent to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> after the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved it Monday on a 326-2 vote, which would be far above the two-thirds majority needed to override any veto. However, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> margin last week was just 48-30, indicating that a veto could be sustained there. The Veterans Administration opposes the bill and says there is no direct evidence proving that the veterans' exposure is causing current health problems. The bill was part of a larger measure authorizing benefits for some 2.7 million veterans. But it was stripped out after administration officials said they would recommend a veto of the overall bill because of the `` atomic veterans'' provision. The measure would cover an estimated 250,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military personnel who were in <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION> after <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> atomic bombs were dropped on those Japanese cities in August 1945, or who took part in open-air tests of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nuclear weapons in the southern <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> or in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> after the war. Many have health problems which they say are related to their radiation exposure. But the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> says they ca n't get disability benefits unless they can show a direct link to their service duty The bill establishes a presumptive link and sets out 13 types of cancers for which the veterans could receive disability payments. According to Rep. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowland </PERSON>, D-Ga., the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> has only allowed 44 of the 6,000 claims filed by atomic veterans The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, Rep. G.V. <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON>, D-Miss., said the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION>'s standard ca n't be met because `` the level of exposure can not be verified. He said that during the tests, some personnel did n't wear radiation-monitoring badges, other servicemen lost their badges and some badges were found to be ineffective. Rep. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> McEwen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ohio </LOCATION>, called the bill `` a reasonable and modest approach'' to the problem. `` If we err in our approach, and I think we do not, then we err on the side of compassion,'' he said.
