<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Audrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Deetz </PERSON> thought her traveling days were over when she was diagnosed as having emphysema. But this week she's packing for her third <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> cruise, accompanied by a hospital medical team. For the third year, <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospitals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cleveland </ORGANIZATION> is sending a doctor, nurses and therapists on a week-long cruise with a group of people with chronic lung diseases. The trip begins Sunday from <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION> with ports of call including <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Grand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cayman </LOCATION>. `` You might say we're all in the same boat,'' said the 73-year-old Ms. <PERSON> Deetz </PERSON>. `` We all have something in common. We understand each other's problems.'' Dr. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Nochomovitz </PERSON>, medical director of the hospital's <ORGANIZATION> Pulmonary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treatment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, said many people with breathing problems are afraid to travel because of their unstable health `` They live for years with the anxiety of something happening suddenly,'' said <PERSON> Nochomovitz </PERSON>, who went on the first two trips. `` Cruise lines are not equipped to handle complex medical illnesses and you ca n't expect them to be.'' He said the hospital-sponsored cruise developed after a patient brought up the problem of traveling. Besides the patient's fear, there's the problem of carrying oxygen supplies and other medical equipment along, he said. Some airlines and cruise lines wo n't allow the equipment, a situation that <PERSON> Nochomovitz </PERSON> wants changed. `` Somehow we've got to set up a system to accommodate these people so they can live as near as normal lives as possible,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Universi