<FIRST>r a PM-WritingCure     05-03 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Writing Cure,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Through Writing, Ex-Mental Patient Finds A Cure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN GEORGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some people write as a hobby, scribbling in journals or dashing off verse and short stories for nothing more than their own pleasure. Others, be they authors of flashy ad campaigns, creators of TV sitcoms or this year's <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON>, are blessed with enough talent and good fortune to do it for money. But <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Garner </PERSON>, a mental patient-turned-poet and songwriter, uses his typewriter to exorcise the demons that led him to two nervous breakdowns and a bout with alcoholism. `` It's been the real savior for me, writing,'' he says, `` because it gave me a chance to bring out my inner feelings.'' <PERSON> Garner </PERSON>, 55, of <LOCATION> Chattanooga </LOCATION>, is the author of `` Deep Within,'' a recently published collection of poetry, and a gospel music album, `` Polished by the Master,'' to be released this month. His voice deliberate and thoughtful, his eyes lively, there's little in <PERSON> Garner </PERSON>'s demeanor to suggest his rocky past But his work is the culmination of a journey that began 28 years ago at <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Robins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. That's where <PERSON> Garner </PERSON> was stationed when he suffered his first nervous breakdown. Although granted an honorable discharge after observation by military officials, he soon checked into a <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> mental hospital in <LOCATION> Murfreesboro </LOCATION>. The doctors diagnosed him as a paranoid schizophrenic: He suffered from feelings of persecution marked by flights of fantasy, illogical thinking and hallucinations. `` I would be depressed one moment, then I'd go to another extreme and be as high as a kite,'' he said. He spent three months in locked confinement. Then another patient suggested he enter a Hospitalized Veterans Writing Project contest. Reluctantly, he submitted an article. Then another, and some short stories and poetry. Nearly all focused on his illness. One poem, `` The Apple,'' read in part: `` Take an apple from a tree; Pretend that apple is me; Now cut the apple in half, Hear one part cry, one part laugh!'' He won some prizes, but that was n't the important thing. Putting the words down seemed to release something within him. `` The more I wrote, the better I felt,'' <PERSON> Garner </PERSON> said. In 1965, after five years of hospitalization, he was discharged. `` I literally wrote myself out of the hospital,'' he said. Two years later, he met and married <PERSON> Helen </PERSON>, his wife of 21 years. He suffered another nervous breakdown and was hospitalized for three months in 1972, but he has n't been back in the hospital. <PERSON> Garner </PERSON>'s work has appeared in numerous poetry anthologies, and he has published two collections of short stories. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON>, whose G & amp; G Publishers of <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> published `` Deep Within,'' remembered his first impression of <PERSON> Garner </PERSON>'s poetry. `` He was almost like an inner soul crying out,'' <PERSON> Green </PERSON> said. `` There was something there that really sort of got to me.'' <PERSON> Garner </PERSON> does n't expect his efforts to make him rich. But he figures he's already done pretty well. `` I want to tell people what I went through so it may help someone else who may say, ` Well, this is the end. I had a nervous breakdown, and this is the end of the world,''' he said. `` But it is n't the end. It's just the beginning.''
</TEXT>
