ber 1 and 4 and that the No. 3 engine was also malfunctioning. `` For this reason, the pilot turned off the number 1 and 4 engines at about 2:00 p.m. and 2:40 p.m. -LRB- Tuesday local time -RRB- consecutively. After requesting emergency landing permission from control authorities, he turned off engine 3 just before beginning to glide in for a landing.'' A statement released by <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> said in part that about one hour and 15 minutes before the jetliner landed `` it lost power in one of the four engines. About 30 minutes later they lost power to a second engine. And just before landing they lost power to a third engine. The plane landed safely and taxied to the terminal under its own power where the passengers deplaned in a normal fashion. The cause of the incident is still under investigtion.'' The mishap occurred several hours after the government urged Japanese airlines to ground and do maintenance checks on <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 jets of the model that lost part of its fuselage last week on an inter-island flight in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. An official of the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s engineering deparment said the 21 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737s in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> are operated by <ORGANIZATION> All </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> and the airline <PERSON> Nansei </PERSON> <PERSON> Koku </PERSON>.
