<TEXT>
 Artist <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>'s painting, `` The Search,'' believed to be his last canvas, fetched $ 4.84 million _ a record for a work of contemporary art _ in frenzied bidding at <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION>'s Monday night, the auction house said. The auction, which included works put up for sale by various owners as well as artist <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>'s personal collection, brought in $ 25,954,500, a record for an auction of contemporary art, said <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell-Innes </PERSON>, the head of <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION>'s contemporary art department. Record prices were set for works by 12 artists, including <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>, <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>, <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Kline </PERSON>, Cy Twombly, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hockney </PERSON> and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Diebenkorn </PERSON>. Six paintings sold for over $ 1 million, she said. `` The contemporary -LRB- art -RRB- world is now extremely aware of the rarity of these really important paintings,'' she said. `` People are very sensitive to the fact that these paintings wo n't come up again. People know this is their last shot.'' `` I've never seen the bidding as heated as it was this evening,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Mitchell-Innes </PERSON>. The auction of <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>'s personal collection of contemporary art brought in $ 5,115,000, with an untitled painting by Twombly fetching $ 990,000, the highest bid for a Warhol-owned work. <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>'s `` Search,'' a canvas in tones of green, red, yellow, black and white, was bought for $ 4.84 million by an anonyous Japanese dealer, Ms. <PERSON> Mitchell-Innes </PERSON> said. The work, which displays the artist's drip technique as well as paint applied with a brush and spattered, had a pre-sale estimate of $ 3 million to $ 4 million. The previous record for a work of contemporary art sold at