<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The city's finest probably wo n't win any fashion contests with a new uniform they're testing, but at least they wo n't have to shine their shoes, crease their pants or polish their gunbelt buckles. `` It's quite different, but it does n't look that different,'' Police Commissioner <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said Monday as two nervous-looking police officers modeled the new threads. The new uniform will be worn by 135 officers citywide for the next year. If it passes final inspection, the duty jacket, raincoat, shirt, trousers, gunbelt and shoes will become mandatory for the city's 27,000 police officers. The changes reflect <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s busy lifestyle that calls for minimal upkeep, and includes machine washable shirts; pants with a permanent crease; shoes that do n't need to be shined and a gunbelt with a non-tarnish buckle. The new jacket, a lightweight poly-wool blend, has four gold-plated buttons to give it the appearance of a dress coat, but is actually closed by a concealed plastic zipper with a Velcro closure. `` You do n't lose the buttons, and yet you have the traditional appearance of the buttons,'' <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said approvingly. The most visible change is the placement of the Police Department patch on both sleeves of the duty jacket, raincoat and shirts. Currently officers wear the patch only on their right shoulders. `` On the old uniform, if you happened to be facing the wrong way, you would n't know whether this was a police officer or a private security guard in a dark suit,'' <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said. As usual, convenience does n't come cheap. The new uniform costs $ 476, versus the $ 350 for the current uniform. `` This is a great improvement over what I wore,'' <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said, recalling that his leather uniform coat `` was heavy and it was n't warm.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ORANGE BEACH, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Technique does n't count for much when throwing fish, but kissing may help, says the winner of the fourth annual Interstate Mullet Toss. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, won the men's division Sunday by tossing a mullet 111 feet, 7 inches across the state line from <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>. `` We bought a couple of mullet last week,'' <PERSON> King </PERSON> said. `` We tried to make them spiral and be aerodynamic, but it did n't work. You just got ta grab it and throw it.'' A day earlier in the preliminaries, King got off a toss of 171 feet, 6 inches, about 30 feet farther than the record set in 1986. But it wo n't go into the record books because only final round throws qualify. `` I know what happened,'' <PERSON> King </PERSON> said after his shorter toss into a strong head wind. `` I did n't kiss -LRB- the mullet -RRB- today. Yesterday, I kissed him. That helps.'' <PERSON> Vickie </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Thomasville </LOCATION> won the women's competition with a toss of 72 feet, 1 inch. `` I throw one every day,'' Ms. <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> said. `` The first thing I do when I get up is throw a mullet.'' About 200 people attended the competition as part of the <ORGANIZATION> Greater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beach </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Mullet </PERSON> are about 8 to 10 inches long and popular for fish fries along the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Panhandle </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> coast. Appropriately enough, mullet are related to flying fish.
