<FIRST>r a PM-Arthritis Bjt   05-03 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arthritis, Bjt,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arthritis Gene Identified In Mice; Early Step Toward Human Cure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Researchers seeking to cure crippling diseases like arthritis and multiple sclerosis in humans say they've taken an early, important step by isolating the gene that causes a form of arthritis in mice. `` We are on the way to finding the cure for this type of arthritis in mice,'' <PERSON> Tariq </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Haqqi </PERSON>, a molecular biologist at the <ORGANIZATION> Mayo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clinic </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, said Monday. If the same kinds of arthritis-causing genes _ or inherited blueprints _ can be identified in humans, `` we are one step closer to the cure and prevention of human rheumatoid arthritis and other human auto-immune diseases'' in which the body apparently is attacked by its own disease-fighting immune system, <PERSON> Haqqi </PERSON> said. Discovery of the gene Vb6 that causes mouse arthritis was outlined by <PERSON> Haqqi </PERSON> during the annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Societies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Experimental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Biology </ORGANIZATION>, which drew 22,000 scientists and exhibitors. The discovery is `` very exciting'' because it is the first time scientists have isolated a gene that causes arthritis, said Dr. <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrison </PERSON> <PERSON> Fathman </PERSON>, an immunologist-rheumatologist at <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. But he said it still will take scientists years to find a cure for rheumatoid arthritis, which afflicts 7 million Americans, or any of the other 100 forms of arthritis and related diseases such as lupus, multiple sclerosis and juvenile or insulin-dependent diabetes. <PERSON> Fathman </PERSON> recently used what are called monoclonal antibodies, proteins made in the laboratory to target specific types of cells, to attack T cells _ a type of white blood cell in the immune system _ that cause diabetes in mice. The mice were cured, he reported Friday in the journal Science. <PERSON> Haqqi </PERSON> is now trying to cure mice of arthritis by using other tailor-made monoclonal antibodies to attack the T cells responsible for that disease without harming other white blood cells, which are needed to defend the body against infection. T cells normally help fight infection by recognizing an invading germ or foreign substance and then triggering production of antibodies to combat them. But bacterial and viral infections also can trigger auto-immune diseases. <PERSON> Haqqi </PERSON> and his colleagues identified and isolated the gene that codes for production of a certain receptor on the surface of T cells in mice. <PERSON> Haqqi </PERSON> said this receptor causes the T cells to lose their ability to distinguish foreign collagen, or connective tissue, from the collagen naturally found in cartilage, tendon and skin. So the T cells attack collagen in cartilage in the mice's joints, causing the inflammation, swelling and pain known as arthritis Scientists from the <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> and from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> also worked on the study, in which mice developed arthritis when injected with collagen from cows. The disease is similar to crippling rheumatoid arthritis in humans. If researchers can identify the genes for human T cell receptors that go awry to cause human arthritis and other auto-immune diseases, `` then we can cure the disease'' and prevent it by producing monoclonal antibodies to attack the culprit T cells while leaving other white blood cells unharmed, <PERSON> Haqqi </PERSON> said. But, he cautioned, `` the antibody that works in mice may not work in humans, so we'll have to find the antibody that works in humans.'' <PERSON> Fathman </PERSON> agreed, saying different monoclonal antibodies would be needed not only for every form of arthritis and auto-immune disease, but possibly for each individual human.
</TEXT>
