<HEAD>South Korea To Begin Producing Anti-AIDS Drug</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A South Korean pharmaceutical company was given permission today to begin mass producing and exporting an anti-AIDS drug at cut-rate prices, officials said. The Health and <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> Samchully </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceutical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> received a permit to manufacture and export Azidothymidine -LRB- AZT -RRB-. But domestic sales of the drug will not be allowed until clinical tests are completed, the ministry said. The drug, first developed in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> as an anti-cancer drug, can lengthen the lives of patients suffering from acquired immune deficiency syndrome by restraining development of the virus that causes the disease. Export plans call for producing the drug at about half the international price of $ 155 for 100 milligrams, officials said. Exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> are expected to begin as early as next month, they said. Plans call for exporting about $ 10 million worth of AZT annually.
