<HEAD>Vietnam Veterans Memorial Defaced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The president of the <ORGANIZATION> Vietnam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> said today that scratches found in the memorial, one resembling a swastika, appear to be random vandalism and not the work of someone trying to make a political statement. `` It looks like the random defacement that happens to memorials in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> from time to time,'' said <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Scruggs </PERSON>. `` The memorial has had about 24 million visitors and only one bad egg.'' The vandalism is the first since the memorial opened in 1982, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> officials said Monday. The 493-foot granite wall inscribed with 58,156 names of those killed in the <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> conflict has become the most visited monument in the nation's capital `` The wall itself has such great respect that we have never had problems with damage,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruback </PERSON>, superintendent of national parks in downtown <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` It had to be someone crazy to do this.'' <PERSON> Ruback </PERSON> said he believed the marks were an act of vandalism. `` Someone stood here and did this on purpose,'' he said, noting that hard objects such as cameras and women's purses often strike the wall without causing any damage. The scratches, about eight inches long, were discovered on a center panel and on a panel near the east end of the memorial early last month. `` We worried about vandalism from the time we began to talk about a memorial,'' said <PERSON> Scruggs </PERSON>, head of the organization that raised money to build the memorial. <PERSON> Scruggs </PERSON> said he has contacted a specialist in polished surfaces to come to inspect the scratches, which he said are not deep. Any nec