<FIRST>r a PM-MonitorSalvage     05-03 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Monitor Salvage,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Engineer Says Uncertain If Civil War Ship Monitor Should Be
Salvaged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An engineer studying the sunken Civil War ship USS Monitor says it could cost $ 20 million to raise the ironclad vessel from its 125-year-old grave off <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, a corrosion and metallurgical engineer with the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hueneme </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, also said that federal officials are uncertain whether to raise the ship. `` Personally, I'd like to make sure anything done there is done carefully so we do n't waste the 120 years that it's been down there,'' <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said Monday at the Offshore Technology Conference here. `` We really do n't know today what could or should be done.'' Already, $ 3 million has been spent on research, and estimates of costs to raise the ship range from $ 10 million to $ 20 million, he said. `` There are major structural components, like the armored deck, the turret, the guns, the engine and the boilers, that appear to be relatively intact and probably could be retrieved,'' he said. On New Year's Eve 1862, the USS Monitor sank in a storm off <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hatteras </LOCATION>. Nine months earlier, on March 9, 1862, it battled the Confederate vessel Merrimack to a draw in the first combat between two ironclad ships. Neither ship was able to inflict serious damage on the other in the battle, which occurred at <LOCATION> Hampton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Roads </LOCATION> off <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. The Merrimack, renamed the <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> by the Confederates, was scuttled two months later when Southern forces abandoned the <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION> navy yard. The Merrimack was discovered in 1910, its armored plates retrieved and sold as souvenirs, <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said. `` We do n't want that to happen to the Monitor, to have pieces of it on the end of keychains,'' he said. `` We do n't want people going in and we do n't want souvenir hunters, a la the Titanic.'' The Monitor suffered extensive damage while being depth-charged during World War II when it mistakenly was believed to be a German submarine. It was not until 1973 that <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> researchers said they believed the wreck was the Monitor. Photographs made two years later confirmed that. Last year, <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> coordinated a corrosion survey of the Monitor, using Norwegian-made electronic probes attached to remote-controlled underwater gear. The probes normally are used to test the corrosion of offshore drilling rigs and the investigation of the Monitor marked one of the first times oilfield technology was applied to marine archeology, he said. The Monitor is in about 230 feet of water, upside down, with its two-gun turret _ made of foot-thick wrought iron and weighing 120 tons _ supporting about 90 feet of the deck above the sea floor. Although corrosion has set in, <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said, it's important to note that less than one-half inch of material has been lost. `` Corrosion rates tend to drop over long periods of time,'' he said. As an engineer, <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said the wreck is significant because it provides corrosion data over 120 years. The wreck in 1975 was designated the first National Marine Sanctuary. <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said technology exists to preserve what it left of the ship or the debris around the vessel could be retrieved or officials can take no action at all. `` We have a lot more plans than money,'' he said. `` Its value is as a fingerprint of society and a fingerprint of shipbuilding in the 1860s.''
</TEXT>
