<HEAD>Letter To Pravda Criticizes Communist Party, Past and Present</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> member harshly criticized his comrades in a letter to Pravda, saying their careerist ambitions and conformity made the party into a mere instrument of <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> and his successors. The letter from a government official, <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Selivanov </PERSON>, to the party daily differed markedly from the usual criticism now seen of the Soviet past, which blames former party leaders themselves for excesses or departures from Marxist-Leninist orthodoxy. <PERSON> Selivanov </PERSON>, deputy chief of administration at the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION>, criticized the 19-million member party itself, and its role in his country's political life since the death of <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> in 1924. <PERSON> Selivanov </PERSON>, a party member since 1972, wrote: `` The party is the mind, honor and conscience of our epoch.'' Those words of V.I. <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> unfortunately can not be applied to all members of our party at the current time.'' His letter, frontpaged in Pravda's Monday editions, appeared the day after May Day, the workers holiday, and its prominent place was clearly designed to give its contents maximum exposure. Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has told party members to back his ambitious program for `` perestroika,'' or social and economic restructuring, or get out of the way for those who do. He is expected to use a party conference on June 28 to set his stamp even more firmly on the party, which holds the monopoly on Soviet political power. `` The main question of perestroika is the democratization of society, and this is not feasible without democratization of the party,'' <PERSON> Selivanov </PERSON> wrote in this letter. To that end, he called for reviewing each <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION>'s past performance to see whether membership should be extended or revoked. The nation's criminal code, now being rewritten, should be modified so Communists who commit crimes get a more severe sentence than non-party members, he said. Party leaders up to the level of regional chief should be elected for a set term by secret ballot, he said. Top local party officials are now appointed by <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, and the appointment ratified by a ritual vote. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> himself floated the idea of a more democratic selection process for local party officials at the party <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s meeting in January 1987. The idea was not repeated in the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s report, indicating a defeat for <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, but it has resurfaced in speeches by Soviet officials. Analyzing the often troubled role of the party during 70 years of Soviet history, <PERSON> Selivanov </PERSON> wrote that during the internecine ideological battles of the late 1920s and 1930s, the party leadership pursued unity `` at any price.'' The result, he said, was the spread of the opinion `` that the GenSec -LRB- party General Secretary -RRB- is always right, that his speeches are the truth, down to the last detail ... it is only necessary to correctly quote the leader.'' During their tenures as party leader, <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> all had no intention of modifying the party structures that concentrated so much power in their hands, <PERSON> Selivanov </PERSON> wrote. For many Communists and their families, the careers, awards, benefits and contacts with influential people they could obtain from their party membership became the chief goals in their lives, he said. In the 1970s, when <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> was in power, <PERSON> Selivanov </PERSON> said some people told him that having intelligence and a conscience was incompatible with being a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>.
