<HEAD>Soviet Panelists Propose 2-Party System, Other Sweeping Changes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> could limit terms of office of high-ranking officials and develop a two-party system in the near future, a panel of Soviet officials said during a conference on U.S.-U.S.S.R. relations. American participants at Monday's conference appeared skeptical upon hearing those and other statements from their Russian counterparts, who outlined plans to revitalize Soviet society after what they called `` 10 years of stagnation.'' `` We are only in the beginning of the process,'' said <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Shislin </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s only political party. `` In five, seven, 10 years _ I do n't know'' how many parties there might be, he said. `` I'd like to see more evidence,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Kessinger </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Goodwill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. He said he'd like to visit the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to see such changes for himself `` If half of what they say is true, there's an amazing thing going on,'' said <PERSON> Kessinger </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Plekhanov </PERSON>, deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Candada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>, said a greater separation of power is part of the goal. `` We are talking about introducing the rule of law in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` But do we want to turn into a litigious society? `` We want