<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 8th and 10th grafs to CORRECT date of primary and
selection of pledged delegates.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are the methods for picking delegates from <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> to attend the 1988 Democratic and Republican national conventions this summer.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Method: Primary Date: Tuesday, May 3 Pledged delegates :159 Super delegates: 15 TOTAL: 174 Delegates allocated: Tuesday, May 3 Selection of delegates: Tuesday, May 3 and Friday, June 10 <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> pick pledged national convention delegates through a presidential preference primary on May 3 The state's 104 pledged delegates from congressional districts will be elected directly from the primary ballot. The presidential candidate receiving the most votes in a congressional district will receive one `` bonus delegate'' from that district and the remaining delegates will be allocated among presidential candidates in proportion to the results of the primary. <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>'s remaining 55 pledged national convention delegates will be chosen by the party's executive committee on June 10 and will be allocated among presidential candidates in proportion to the results of the primary.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Method: Primary Date: Tuesday, May 3 Delegates: 88 Delegates allocated: Tuesday, May 3 Selection of delegates: Tuesday, May 3 Ohio Republicans elect their national convention delegates directly from the May 3 primary ballot. <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> is a winner-take-all state, so the candidate getting the most votes in each congressional district will get all three of the convention delegates from those districts. The remaining 25 delegates at large are awarded to the candidate receiving the most votes statewide.
</TEXT>
