<HEAD>Yeltsin Says Soviet Leaders Must Not Disappoint The Public</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ousted <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Communist Party boss <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yelstin </PERSON> today said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> leadership can not afford to disappoint the nation in the application of its reform campaign. `` This hope must not be deceived, or then it will not be easy to restore faith to the people, to elevate them to great tasks,'' <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> told the daily <ORGANIZATION> Stroitelnaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gazeta </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Construction Newspaper -RRB- in an interview. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>, 57, once considered a protege of Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, was fired as <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> party chief Nov. 11 after criticizing the slow pace of reform and the party's style of leadership at a party meeting. One week after his ouster, <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> was named first deputy chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Construction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, a government job that carries the rank of minister but that is clearly inferior to the post of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> party boss. <PERSON> Stoitelnaya </PERSON> <PERSON> Gazeta </PERSON> sought <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>'s comments in connection with a front-page article on woes in the Soviet contruction industry, which is having to conform to the same cost-cutting and efficiency measures as the rest of the economy. `` The situation here is serious in effect,'' <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> said. `` Thus cardinal changes in our branch are especially needed.'' He said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s economic and social reform program, known as `` perestroika,'' or reconstruction, had reached a `` decisive phase.'' Its success, <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> added, depends on `` the support of the wide masses of workers who hope for changes for the better in their lives and link them with perestroika.'' <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>, who graduated as a construction engineer in 1955 from the <ORGANIZATION> Ural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Polytechnical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Sverdlovsk </LOCATION>, said the reform program could bring quick, beneficial changes in construction. `` What is reconstruction in a position to give people in the near future? I think, first of all, an improvement in housing conditions, growth in the number of up-to-date medical installations, schools and kindergartens,'' <PERSON> Yelstin </PERSON> said. Housing is an acute problem in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, where one family in five lives in dormitories or communal dwellings. A party program has called for the construction of enough new housing so each family will have its own home or apartment by the year 2000. Although the article printed in <LOCATION> Stoitelnaya </LOCATION> Gazeta made no reference to <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>'s stormy political career, he defended the criticisms he had made at the October meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> in an interview published abroad last month. `` I spoke in a straightforward manner and said what I felt and thought was correct,'' <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> said. `` Someone said correctly: each must think independently so that later not all suddenly see the light at once.'' That interview was published in the inaugural edition of a German-language version of the state-run weekly <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, which was printed and distributed in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>'s comments were not reproduced in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> News' Russian editions.
