<HEAD>Balloon Race Ends, Winners Land in Gulf of California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The pilot and co-pilot of a race balloon that floated perilously for hours above a jagged island in the Gulf of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> landed safely today and were declared the race's winners, officials said. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Kittinger </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sherry </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>, both of <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, were declared the unofficial winners of the annual <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> Balloon Race after they touched down at 3:43 a.m. on Angel de la Guarda island, said race spokeswoman <PERSON> Mildred </PERSON> <PERSON> Brodbeck </PERSON>. Their balloon had floated about 365 miles southeast from its starting point in <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, Ms. <PERSON> Brodbeck </PERSON> said. The pair had declared an emergency shortly after 1 a.m. and called for assistance when their helium balloon began descending over the rough, uninhabited island, Ms. <PERSON> Brodbeck </PERSON> said. `` They ran out of ballast to throw overboard and began dropping about 100 feet a minute,'' she said. `` That's a lot.'' Ballast is made of weights used to control the altitude of such balloons. When the helium in the craft cools, it contracts and loses its lift, said <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Soukup </PERSON>, an official with the <ORGANIZATION> Balloon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>. `` To counteract the sinking, you have to throw ballast, in this case sand and water, overboard,'' he said. A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> jet and a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Customs plane spotted the balloon at about 3 a.m. and stayed nearby in case of a crash landing. Upon touchdown, the jet dropped supplies including a raft, food and water, the spokeswoman said. The couple were believed to have landed near the beach, but that was unconfirmed, Ms. <PERSON> Brodbeck </PERSON> said. The official winners will be announced Saturday night during a `` Survivor's Banquet'' and will receive a trophy designed by <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> editorial cartoonist <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON>, she said. The other six balloons in the race, which left here between 11 p.m. Sunday and 2 a.m. Monday, all landed by Monday afternoon. The winning crew is the one whose balloon lands farthest from the start of the race. Restaurateur <PERSON> Rocky </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoki </PERSON> holds the record for the race, which is named after <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> newspaper publisher <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, who founded the event in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> in 1906. <PERSON> Aoki </PERSON> flew 1,346 miles to <LOCATION> Millarton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.D. </LOCATION>, in 1981. Fickle winds held last year's winner to just 49 miles. Of the other entrants this year, distances ranged from 247 miles down to 42.
