<HEAD>Couple Wins $7.5 Million in Malpractice Suit Against Psychiatrist</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd and 12th grafs, ``Phyllis and xxx, to raise 1st
reference to Rotmans</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A couple has won $ 7.5 million in a malpractice suit against a psychiatrist whose patient killed their 23-year-old daughter. <PERSON> Shelly </PERSON> <PERSON> Rotman </PERSON>, daughter of <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Rotman </PERSON>, was fatally stabbed July 17, 1978, by <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Gould </PERSON>, who was later found innocent of a murder charge by reason of insanity. Dr. <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Merin </PERSON> had treated <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> during the three years before the killing when he was medical director of a private psychiatric hospital. <PERSON> Merin </PERSON> called the verdict `` shocking and regrettable'' because he said he believed he had done `` everything I humanly could do with the resources available to me to make sure <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> did not kill <PERSON> Shelly </PERSON> <PERSON> Rotman </PERSON>.'' His lawyer, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Reidy </PERSON>, said he may appeal. <PERSON> Merin </PERSON> said a number of psychiatric hospitals had treated and discharged <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> between the time he was diagnosed as psychotic in 1973 and the slaying. According to testimony, <PERSON> Merin </PERSON> warned Ms. <PERSON> Rotman </PERSON> in a letter in August 1976 that <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> had talked of harming her. <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> had dated her for about one year before his breakdown. He believed he was a messiah and that he had to kill Ms. <PERSON> Rotman </PERSON> to save the Jewish people, according to testimony. He continuously tried to contact her between 1973 and 1978, but she did not return his telephone calls and tried to avoid him, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>, the Rotmans' lawyer. <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> argued that <PERSON> Merin </PERSON> should have hospitalized <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> while he had psychotic delusions about Ms. <PERSON> Rotman </PERSON> and that his letter of warning should have been stronger and more explicit. Ms. <PERSON> Rotman </PERSON> was stabbed when she arrived at a Quincy nursing home where she worked. The Rotmans were awarded $ 4.5 million by a <ORGANIZATION> Middlesex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> jury. Interest payments will add $ 3 million to the award. <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> has been a patient at <ORGANIZATION> Bridgewater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> since the slaying.
