<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The third convoy of U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tankers in five days headed up the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> today as the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> tried to make up for time lost to a mine threat and fighting with Iranian forces. The convoy got under way as Adm. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Staff </ORGANIZATION>, arrived in the gulf to inspect <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> operations and confer with Rear Adm. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> A </PERSON>. Less, commander of the Joint Task Force <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, and other senior officers. <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> was expected to meet with top officials of <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> governments in the gulf to outline the latest change in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy that will permit <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> warships to respond to requests for help from non-U.S. flag vessels under attack by the Iranians. Shipping industry and government officials in general have reacted favorably to the change in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> `` rules of engagement.'' These had previously restricted commanders to protecting only American-flagged ships and giving only `` humanitarian aid'' to others if requested. The latest convoy was confirmed by a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military spokesman hours after shipping executives reported it sailing through the <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION> into the gulf for <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>. It included the 294,739-ton <PERSON> Townsend </PERSON> and the <LOCATION> 81,283-ton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Isle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCAT