<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Transit,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Paralyze Road Traffic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A guerrilla-imposed road transport ban, the third this year, drastically curtailed traffic nationwide today. Not a single city bus was seen circulating downtown in a rush-hour tour of the capital <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. Buses are by far the most important mode of public transport in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. Circulation of privately owned cars was a fraction of that on a normal day. Thousands of workers left home early and walked, often several miles, to their jobs. Many owners of vans and pickups converted them to public transports, charging 40 cents, about six times the average bus fare. Virtually all of the pickups and vans were overcrowded. During the previous transport ban in March, the overcrowding caused several accidents that killed at least one person and injured several others. Leftist guerrillas waging an 8-year-old war against the U.S.-backed government called the indefinite ban in response to what they say is an increase in repression by police and the armed forces. No time limit was put on the measure, although previous bans have lasted two or three days. The guerrillas enforce the ban by firing on or burning buses, trucks and private cars. On their clandestine Radio Venceremos, they warn drivers that guerrillas and their supporters will be taking down license plate numbers and that retaliation could come at any time in the future. Dispatchers at the capital's two main intercity bus terminals said no buses had arrived from or left for provincial cities. Gen. <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Blandon </PERSON>, chief of the joint chiefs of staff, said Monday night that all leaves for members of the 56,000-strong armed forces had been canceled to provide security along the nation's roads and highways In previous strikes, the army has put its trucks into service as public transport. A few were seen on city streets this morning, but not as many as in previous bans.
</TEXT>
