<FIRST>r a PM-InmateScam     05-03 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Inmate Scam,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homosexuals Primary Victims of Prisoners' Postal Money Order Scam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARCHMAN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Men who answered ads in homosexual magazines were the primary victims of a $ 330,000 postal money order scam run by seven current and former <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> state penitentiary inmates, officials said. The inmates and four other people, including several relatives of the prisoners, have been charged by the federal government in the scam. The April 22 indictments resulted from a probe by <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> postal inspectors that began in 1986. The scheme, officials said, involved the changing of 800 U.S. Postal money orders between September 1986 and last month. <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> inmates using similar scams have cleared $ 5 million over the past six years, officials estimate, and the schemes have spread to other state prisons in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind </LOCATION>. There have been 35 convictions connected with the scams. According to the recent indictments, inmates wrote to those who had either placed or responded to personal advertisements in magazines. Inmates used fake names and claimed to be in prison on minor charges, such as drunken driving. Two inmates would then call the individuals who responded and pose as the inmate's case worker, social worker or lawyer. Eventually, victims were asked to cash money orders from the `` case worker'' and send the money to a third party. The non-inmates involved in the scheme would buy money orders for between $ 1 and $ 5, then deliver them to the inmates, who would alter the value to amounts up to $ 700. The people who received the money orders never knew they had been altered, officials said. They would cash them for the altered amounts and mail the money; the non-inmates involved would then forward it to the inmates. Of more than 25 victims caught in the scheme by inmates, <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> postal inspector <PERSON> J.R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Argubright </PERSON> said, `` the majority of victims were from homosexual-oriented magazines.'' For the last three years, the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penitentiary </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Parchman </LOCATION> has stamped all prisoners' letters with the warning that recipients should not cash any money orders enclosed, state corrections department <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. However, prisoners circumvent this precaution by sending letters to co-conspirators outside prison, who mail them in other envelopes.
