 <PERSON> Pauline </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> says her body is so full of electricity that she knocks out ordinary household appliances with a mere touch. She says she is one of about 40 people in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> who are similarly afflicted, and the experts are baffled. The Sun newspaper, which interviewed the 46-year-old housewife, calculated that she has wrecked 25 household irons, 18 toasters, 15 kettles, 6 tumble dryers, 10 washing machines, 12 television receivers, 12 radios, 3 videos and at least 250 lightbulbs. The total damage, the Sun calculated, is about $ 13,000. Mrs. <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> says she does n't bother to count anymore. `` I do n't touch the video or the microwave,'' she said in a telephone interview Tuesday from her home in <LOCATION> Manchester </LOCATION>. `` I cook only with gas.'' She said she lost her job at the counter of a drycleaning store `` because I was making the tills go haywire.'' She said she once knocked out her bank's computer by leaning on a terminal. Mrs. <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> said she has suffered from body electricity since childhood, but it worsened in 1982. `` It's not a party trick, something I do at will. It comes suddenly, by itself. You can get quite a sharp shock shaking my hand.'' Doctors who have examined her think it may be caused by an allergy or stress, `` but I'm not a tense person. I'm a noisy, sense-of-humor kind of person,'' she said. <PERSON> Mrs. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON>, a bus-driver's wife with three children, said the only solution she has come up with is to shower three times a day. `` It washes the electricity off the skin,'' she said.
