<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Jews said today a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> rabbi had been chosen to head their community on an interim basis, but the rabbi said he had yet to receive an invitation and did n't know whether he would go to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> also denied that such an arrangement had been made. However, Rabbi <PERSON> Ernst </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorge </PERSON>, contacted in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, said he would be willing to consider a short-term arrangement. `` I have not yet received an official invitation to come to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, and if I do I would have to think about it,'' said <PERSON> Lorge </PERSON>, 71. `` I might accept something shorter in term ... My life is here in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. I imagine with some understanding we could come to some kind of agreement.'' At issue is a successor for Rabbi <PERSON> Isaac </PERSON> <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON>, who is leaving <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> after an eight-month tenure marked by several disputes with the city's Jewish community president. Sources within the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Jewish community told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that President <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirchner </PERSON> had received a letter from the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> naming <PERSON> Lorge </PERSON> as interim successor for <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Kirchner </PERSON> has confirmed that <LOCATION> Lorge </LOCATION> is going to be the new rabbi. But he will be a rabbi on an interim basis, until a permanent rabbi can be found,'' sources close to the Jewish community president said. They said Jewish leaders have in mind a rabbi in his 30s as a permanent successor, but declined to elaborate. The sources spoke on condition of anonymity. <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> DuBow </PERSON>, director of community services for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, denied that such an arrangement had been made with <PERSON> Lorge </PERSON>. `` There is no truth to the report that he is coming,'' <PERSON> DuBow </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. He said <PERSON> Lorge </PERSON> had been a guest rabbi in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> during the High Holidays in the past. <PERSON> Lorge </PERSON>, who was born in <LOCATION> Mainz </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and emigrated to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to flee Nazi persecution in 1936, said he wanted to help <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s Jewish community. `` I have a philosophy that <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> should not get a posthumous victory _ that there should not be any country where Jews are not able to have any kind of community,'' he said. <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON> complained last weekend of interference from leadership of the local Jewish community and outlined differences with the communist government over funding. He said he would leave <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> on May 16 and might return in September, but not to work. Jewish leaders, in a statement to the official East German news agency <ORGANIZATION> ADN </ORGANIZATION>, denied they meddled in <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON>'s activities. `` The assertion that Rabbi <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON> was hindered in carrying out his functions by members, or the community repr