<HEAD>Census Needs 35,000 Temporary Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Help Wanted. Thirty-five thousand openings. Must be detail-oriented. Pays $ 5.50-an-hour, plus mileage. Outdoor work, no heavy lifting. The <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> is gearing up for the 1990 national head count, and it needs people to help compile the address list for use in mailing out the forms when the time comes. Workers will go door-to-door to compile some 32 million addresses this year, and will add another 11 million next year, officials said Tuesday. Most of the work is in counties away from metropolitan areas. Lists of the 56 million addresses in large cities are being purchased from commercial mailing-list companies. Those compiling the address lists will work for about six weeks, the <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> said, with the effort starting in July in 18 states. The compilation will continue through December, moving to other states as the first ones are completed. Applicants must take a written exam. Interested persons can get details from their local state employment office or by writing Field Division, <ORGANIZATION> Room </ORGANIZATION> 3005-3, <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> 20233. The address list will be used to send census forms to households in the spring of 1990, and then to double check which ones have been returned and which require follow-up visits. At that time an even bigger hiring effort is planned, because some 400,000 temporary workers will be needed for the census itself.
