<HEAD>Grand Jury Returns No Indictments in MOVE Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A special grand jury today called city officials' conduct in the 1985 MOVE siege that led to 11 deaths `` totally unacceptable,'' but returned no criminal indictments in what it called the city's greatest tragedy. Eleven people died and 61 homes were destroyed on May 13, 1985, when police dropped a bomb on a barricaded west <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> row house occupied by the radical group MOVE. `` Applying the law to the facts as we find them, no charges are warranted, yet we do not exonerate the men responsible for this disaster,'' the grand jury said in its 279-page report. `` Rather than a vindication of those officials, this report should stand as a permanent record of their morally reprehensible behavior. `` This city, its leaders and citizens, must never forget the terrible cost of their misjudgments.'' The confrontation started after neighbors who had been targets of threats and harassment for several years told authorities they would try to evict MOVE themselves unless the city acted. The grand jury report, released this afternoon, denounced the city's planning for and actions in the siege as incompetent and inept. It especially castigated Mayor <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> <PERSON> Goode </PERSON>. `` As the city's chief executive officer and the man legally responsible for law enforcement in the city, <PERSON> Goode </PERSON> delegated too much, deferred too often, and asked too few questions,'' the report said. The MOVE group championed back-to-nature rituals, lived in filth with rats and other animals, refused to send their children to school and disobeyed health and safety laws. It was decimated by the disaster, and most of its living members are now in jail. The report said other top officials also were uninformed, including the city's No. 2 executive at the time, former Managing Director <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON>. During the confrontation, when police gunfire failed to drive out the MOVE members, <P