<HEAD>Doctors Separate Siamese Twins Joined At Head</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Doctors separated 17-month-old Siamese twins, joined at the head, in an intricate operation Tuesday that took 7 -LCB- hours, officials at <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Baragwanath </ORGANIZATION> hospital reported. They described the surgery by a 40-member medical team on <PERSON> Mpho </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mphonyana </PERSON> <PERSON> Mathibela </PERSON> as successful. The hospital is in the huge black township outside <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sophie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mathibela </PERSON>, mother of the girls, said: `` I feel so happy. ... I want to sleep a little, pray and thank <PERSON> God </PERSON> for all he has done.'' A statement by the hospital said <PERSON> Mpho </PERSON>, the stronger of the two, was doing well but <PERSON> Mphonyana </PERSON> suffered extensive blood loss and was in critical condition. It did not elaborate. Last September, doctors at <LOCATION> Johns </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hopkins </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, separated West German twins joined at the head. The two boys, <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Binder </PERSON>, survived and were released in March, but are said to have some physical and mental problems. <PERSON> Johns </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> doctors advised those at <LOCATION> Baragwanath </LOCATION> on the difficulties they were likely to face. Members of the medical team performed two operations on the girls last October in preparation for Tuesday's surgery. In those operations, doctors partially clamped a shared major blood vessel in the twins' heads in hopes that lesser blood vessels would take over its functions. Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lipschitz </PERSON>, chief of the surgical team, told a news conference last Friday chances for success were not good. `` This is going to be a ... lengthy, intricate operation which carries many dangers with it,'' he said. `` The prognosis is still very grave.'' Ms. <PERSON> Mathibela </PERSON>, an unmarried, 33-year-old domestic worker who earns about $ 60 a month, gave birth to the twins Dec. 7, 1986. She attended a prayer service in the hospital chapel Tuesday morning. About 100 people, most of them nurses and patients, said prayers and sang hymns for the girls. The mother said she had been horrified by giving birth to Siamese twins and refused to see the girls for three days, but `` once persuaded to see them, I immediately accepted and loved my little gifts from God.'' They had a combined weight of 33 pounds before the surgery. <PERSON> Mpho </PERSON> appears to be developing normally and recently began to speak, but <PERSON> Mphonyana </PERSON> is slightly smaller and does not appear to be as advanced, said officials at <LOCATION> Baragwanath </LOCATION>, the main hospital in <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Mathibela </PERSON> was asked to make a $ 5 contribution to the costs of the operations and related care, which will total hundreds of thousands. The costs are being absorbed by the hospital and the <ORGANIZATION> Witwatersrand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> medical school. The Sowetan, a daily newspaper that covers the black township, established a trust fund for the twins and the equivalent of about $ 26,000 has been raised.
