<HEAD>Healthy Breakfast Tied to Higher Test Scores</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A healthy breakfast helped <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> students score higher on tests, according to a study released Tuesday. About 1,000 children in third through sixth grades from six schools were involved in the study conducted by two <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> pediatricians. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyers </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Weitzman </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> presented their findings Tuesday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, at the annual research meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Ambulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pediatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. They hope to encourage colleagues to push for a national breakfast program. `` Only a handful of states besides <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> mandate the breakfast program,'' said <PERSON> Meyers </PERSON>. `` We are trying to give these kids every break they can have. It looks like there may be some benefit here.'' <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> ordered communities with large numbers of poor families to begin school breakfasts in January 1987. The Lawrence study began three months after the law took effect. Test scores from 335 children in the program were compared to scores from 688 children who were not. Almost all the children were from poor families. Among the results: _ Test scores showed greater improvement for children in the breakfast program. Their scores went up 13.5 percent the following year, compared to 11 percent for children not in the program. _ Children in the program were late or absent less frequently, and breakfast eaters made fewer mistakes in the morning. School lunches are now available to most <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> children, but breakfast is offered to about 40 percent. The study estimates about 600,000 children skip breakfast every day. Cost is a problem. The federal government spent $ 400 million in 1986 to serve breakfast to 33,000 public school students, <PERSON> Meyers </PERSON> said.
