<HEAD>Ousted Moscow Official Joins Chorus Of Commentary On Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ousted <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Communist Party boss <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> returned to the spotlight Tuesday to join a chorus of critics of the status quo and to support Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s economic restructuring drive. In an article in the daily Construction Gazette, <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> called on Soviet workers to make the reforms work. He also warned the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leadership that it should be careful not to deceive the people and make them lose faith. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>, who gained wide popularity in the capital with his raids on food stores and personal inspection of public transit, was fired as <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> party leader on Nov. 11 after he criticized the slow pace of reforms during a closed-door meeting of the party <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. His ouster sent a chill through the ranks of reformists, who worried that <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>'s removal signaled strong resistance to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s efforts at allowing more openness about problems plaguing Soviet society. A week after losing the party job, <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> was named first deputy chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Construction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which carries ministerial rank but falls far short of the influence he enjoyed as <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> party leader. Construction <PERSON> Gazette </PERSON> sought <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>'s comments in connection with a front-page article on woes in the Soviet contruction industry, which is having to conform to the same cost-cutting and efficiency measures as the rest of the economy under the `` perestroika,'' or rebuilding, campaign. It made no reference to his former party job. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> told the newspaper that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms are at a `` decisive phase,'' and that the leadership should be careful to fulfill the hopes and expectations of the working people. `` This hope must not be deceived, or then it will not be easy to restore faith to the people, to elevate them to great tasks,'' <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> said. Success, he said, depends on `` the support of the wide masses of workers who hope for changes for the better in their lives and link them with perestroika.'' He said the reforms could produce some long-needed improvements in the near future, including better housing, more modern medical facilities and more schools and kindergartens. Housing is still an acute problem in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, where one family in five lives in dormitories or communal dwellings. A party program has called for the construction of enough new housing so each family will have its own home or apartment by the year 2000. The Construction Gazette article was the first mass-circulation Soviet publication to quote <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> since his departure from the party job. Last month, the inaugural German-language edition of the weekly <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> carried an interview with him. That publication is printed and distributed abroad. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>'s public return came a day after the party daily Pravda published on its front page a letter from another government official, who criticized his fellow party members for pursuing careerist ambitions over the ideals set down by Soviet founder <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>. The official, identified as <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Selivanov </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION>, contended that party members have tainted <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>'s postulate that `` The party is the mind, honor and conscience of our epoch.'' He called for improvements within the party as well as industry and society as part of the restructuring campaign and introduction of more democracy in Soviet life. Tuesday night's edition of the government newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> carried a lengthy criticism of Soviet industry and agriculture. Prominent author <PERSON> Chingiz </PERSON> <PERSON> Aitmatov </PERSON> said Soviets continue to justify poor production with weak excuses about losses suffered during World War II, although countries like <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> hit even harder long ago outdistanced Soviet performance. <PERSON> Aitmatov </PERSON>, a popular writer whose literary works attack totalitarianism, said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms hold out the only hopes for improving Soviet farm and factory output. The commentaries on democratic and economic reforms appear to be part of the preparations for next month's party conference, at which <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> will seek broader endorsement for his campaigns and likely remove some of the more conservative forces fighting the changes he has advocated. The criticism of social and economic progress to date voiced by <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Selivanov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Aitmatov </PERSON>, and their calls for support for <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms, embrace the leader's two main themes of greater openness and a wholesale rebuilding of the nation.
