<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON> is ready to share power with the opposition in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> after his party's losses in legislative elections, party officials said Tuesday. Officials of <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> said they wanted to reach an agreement with the opposition soon so the new <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> can hold its opening session around May 20. `` We would favorably consider an opposition demand that the parliamentary leadership be shared by parties according to their assembly seats,'' the governing party's floor leader, <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Yoon-hwan </PERSON>, said after meeting with senior party leaders. Opposition candidates made a strong showing in legislative elections a week ago, stripping the government party of its parliamentary majority for the first time in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s modern history. The three opposition parties took 164 seats in the 299-member assembly. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>'s party won 125 seats, 25 shy of a simple majority. A handful of independent candidates also won seats. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON>, who was appointed floor leader in a shakeup of the party's leadership on Monday, said formal discussions of the new Assembly's leadership could start after opposition parties hold their national conventions next <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> said the government party wants to hold the speakership but would cede the two vice speaker's posts to the opposition. Traditionally, only one vice speaker's post has been left to the opposition. The chairmanships of 13 assembly committees should also be shared with the opposition, <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> said. In the past, all committees were headed by governing party members. After the legislative elections, the president said he would `` humbly'' accept the outcome. He added he would work with the opposition to continue to carry out his promises for democratic reforms. In a first move to reorganize the government camp after the election, <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> replaced the head of his party with a moderate senior politician. Other senior party posts also were filled with moderates. Government officials said <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> was expected to shake up his <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION>, probably next week, but leave Prime Minister <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyun-hae </PERSON> in place. Opposition leader <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Dae-jung </PERSON>, whose <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> emerged as the No. 1 opposition force in the elections, said he would like to delay debates on controversial issues if they would disrupt the 1988 Olympics in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>.
