<SECOND>AM-AIDS Pamphlet, Bjt,920</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Set To Kick Off AIDS Alert Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal officials on Wednesday will kick off an intensive three-week campaign to alert Americans about AIDS, focused around the mailing of a pamphlet on the deadly disease to every household in the nation. Health and Human Services Secretary <PERSON> Otis </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON>, Surgeon General <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> and other top administration health leaders scheduled a news conference to officially unveil the booklet, whose contents were being kept secret Tuesday. The promotional campaign _ including television spots and posters in each of the nation's post offices _ is designed to alert Americans to be looking for the historic pamphlet when it starts showing up in mailboxes May 26. It will be the first time the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government has sent a health advisory directly to every American with a mailing address. The secrecy surrounding the actual content of the document stems from decision by department officials to apply a strict reading to congressional directions ordering that a national mailing be undertaken by June 30. That language in the omnibus budget bill covering the current fiscal year said the mailing was to be prepared and `` distributed without necessary clearance of the content by any official, organization or office.'' Although health department officials have been wary of discussing preparation of the document, they have acknowledged that they interpreted the wording to mean that the pamphlet's content should not be subject to prior scrutiny either by the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> itself. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> called for a similar mailing last year, but with less explicit language. That project was never completed, in part because of objections raised by some White House officials. One of the reasons given was that because President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had just appointed a White House AIDS commission to make recommendations on overall AIDS policy, it would be appropriate for the panel to review any mailing. However, the commission did not get into the issue at the time on grounds that it was just beginning its work and was not ready to examine specific inititives. The panel was not asked to review the current mailing and did not ask to be involved. `` The commission has not formally or informally been involved in the planning or preparation or writing of this booklet,'' spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Brandt </PERSON> said Tuesday in an interview. He said retired <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Adm. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> and the panel's executive director `` are familiar with some elements of it, but like everybody else in town they are waiting to see it and hope it is successful. AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a contagious, incurable isease that attacks the body's immune system, rendering it incapable of resisting other diseases and infections. The virus most often is spread through close contact with blood, blood products or semen from infected persons. The disease's chief victims have been homosexual men and intravenous drug users, with a small percentage of cases attributed to transfusions of contaminated blood, heterosexual contact and spread from infected pregnant women to their offspring. As of April 21, AIDS had been diagnosed in about 59,500 Americans, of whom more than half, or about 33,000 have died since June 1981, according to the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Kline </PERSON> said the pamphlet will be `` as complete as it can be within a relatively constrained format, discussing AIDS in terms of how you can get AIDS, how you ca n't get AIDS, the various precautions that can be taken, beginning of course with avoiding risky behavior.'' He said there are sections on AIDS and children, AIDS and dating, babies with AIDS `` and on people with AIDS and the rights they have and the obligations owed to them.'' Asked specifically whether it will mention condoms, <PERSON> Kline </PERSON> said: `` This particular mailer addresses all aspects of AIDS and how it is communicated and how one can avoid _ or if not avoid, at least provide the best protection for the circumstances.'' Since 1986, when he issued a 36-page surgeon general's report on AIDS, <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> has been the administration's most vocal advocate of condom use for sexually active people who are not in monogomous relationships. That booklet has been distributed to an estimated 19 million Americans _ many via mail from individual members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> who requested copies to mail to their constituents. The basic themes laid down in the 1986 report have been repeated in subsequent <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> documents. The outspoken <PERSON> Koop </PERSON>'s planned presence at the Wednesday announcement was an indication the mailing will adhere to the approach he has been taking on AIDS education and prevention. His spokesman, <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, declined to say what role <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> had played in preparation of the mailer or whether it will state the surgeon general's position on condom use. `` It would be really difficult to leave out the surgeon general who has been the voice of this administration speaking out on AIDS since he was first asked to do the -LRB- 1986 -RRB- report by the president,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said in an interview. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> noted that Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Windom </PERSON>, the No. 2 official in the health department, and <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> Undersecretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Newman </PERSON> will be making a simultaneous announcement of the mailing Wednesday in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. `` We discovered when we were in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> in January -LRB- for an AIDS conference attended by health ministers from almost every country in the world -RRB- that there was a great deal of concern about what the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was doing,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. `` We thought this was a good opportunity to show them what we're doing now in addition to all the things we have done before.''
