<HEAD>Bottom Line on Warhol Auction: $25 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ten days of <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warhol-mania </PERSON> ended Tuesday when <PERSON> Sotheby </PERSON>'s auction house brought down the last gavel on its sale of the late artist's personal collection. The grand total: $ 25.3 million. The sale, which featured more than 10,000 items owned by <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>, attracted an estimated 60,000 people to the Sotheby galleries and set tongues wagging and jaws dropping throughout the art world. Proceeds from the auction vastly exceeded <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION>'s official pre-auction estimate of $ 9 million to $ 13 million. While auction house officials admitted that they purposely underestimated the collection's value, they expressed surprise over the extent of the miscalculation. `` Our feeling when we figured the estimates was that we would n't add any ` Warhol factor,''' said <PERSON> Diana </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> `` I think what we're seeing today is an indication not only of the ` Warhol factor' but of a very strong art market.'' For whatever reason, buyers were willing to pay dearly for just about anything owned by <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>, who died in February 1987 and owned many, many things. Sales figures included $ 2,640 for three plastic watches bearing the likenesses of <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Flintstone </PERSON>, <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Jetson </PERSON> and Gumby; $ 23,000 for a pair of cookie jars; $ 55,000 for a set of <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dali </LOCATION> ear clips; and $ 605,000 for a <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lichtenstein </PERSON> painting, `` Sailboats.'' Proceeds from the auction go to the <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> Foundation for the <ORGANIZATION> Visual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION>, which was established by the artist to support cultural institutions. The highest-priced item at the sale was an untitled 1967 painting by <PERSON> Cy </PERSON> <PERSON> Twombley </PERSON> that fetched $ 990,000 _ a record for a work by that artist. It was one of many records set during the marathon sale. Works of art routinely sold for double or triple _ or more _ their estimated value. A <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hockney </PERSON> drawing of <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>, valued at $ 60,000 to $ 80,000, sold for $ 330,000 _ an example of the `` Warhol factor'' working overtime. `` It's a joke to attempt to buy here,'' complained one <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> art dealer, <PERSON> Geert </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Veen </PERSON>. `` I do n't think there are many dealers who could touch those prices _ or want to. You'd look crazy.'' `` I think the prices have no relation to the value,'' said another dealer, <PERSON> Ames </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Manchester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vt. </LOCATION> `` The <LOCATION> Warhol </LOCATION> imprimatur is just inflating prices irrationally.'' <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Veen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> both said that private collectors, not art dealers, were doing most of the buying at the <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> auction _ something Sotheby's officials disputed. `` For those of us who buy for resale, or for investment, it's not a very attractive auction,'' said <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> But for others, the <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> auction was exceedingly attractive. `` It's not an exaggeration to say this was a historic event,'' said <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Deitch </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Private </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, who buys art on behalf of bank clients. `` A lot of the prices sound high to the casual bidder, but they're not insanely high,'' <PERSON> Deitch </PERSON> said. `` For instance, in the auction of the Warhol furniture, many of the pieces went for what you'd pay for new furniture.'' Anyway, he said, `` I think it sends an interesting signal that our culture values these things, and I think that as a culture we can feel very good that works of art are valued to this extent.'' <PERSON> Deitch </PERSON> predicted that anything associated with <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> would continue to escalate in value as more people come to appreciate the artist, who remains controversial in death as he was in life. `` It's just beginning,'' he said. `` Just beginning.''
