<HEAD>Appeal of Dearborn Parks Case Heard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A predominantly white suburb should have the right to `` control its own possessions'' by barring non-residents from its parks, a lawyer for the town said Tuesday. A three-judge state <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> panel heard arguments on an appeal of a 1986 ruling overturning a referendum in <LOCATION> Dearborn </LOCATION>. In November 1985, the voters in the town, located on <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s western border, had approved a measure that would ban non-residents from 35 of its 37 parks. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> challenged the law, saying it effectively discriminated against blacks from neighboring <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Saxton </PERSON>, representing <LOCATION> Dearborn </LOCATION>, said Tuesday that the ruling should be overturned because the same argument could be used to strike down a number of other laws that had potential discriminatory effects. `` The plaintiffs are making an abhorrent argument, ...'' he said in an interview outside the hearing. `` The city has a right to control its own possessions.'' But <ORGANIZATION> Wayne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> law Professor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Sedler </PERSON>, who argued in behalf of the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION>, said the ordinance `` is going to make the <LOCATION> Dearborn </LOCATION> parks all white.'' However, he added, the case is limited and should apply only to <LOCATION> Dearborn </LOCATION> parks. `` Our view is a very narrow one,'' he said. In September 1986, <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Circuit Judge <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Stempien </PERSON> ruled that the ban was unconstitutional because of its possibl