<FIRST>r a AM-JockeyTrainer     05-03 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jockey Trainer,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>School Gets Would-Be Jockeys Out Of The Starting Gate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN STRAUSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COMMISKEY, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There's a world of difference between riding a thoroughbred horse and driving a car, but there is also one similarity: Let either one get out of control and you have a problem. `` These horses are a little bit crazy,'' said <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schulte </PERSON>, a former history teacher who is owner of <ORGANIZATION> Hawkeye </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Racing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. `` Students who have had a horse run off with them say it's like being in a Formula One race car with the throttle stuck open, very little steering and no brakes.'' About 70 percent of those in the <LOCATION> Hawkeye </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> riding program wash out because they ca n't master the powerful, high-spirited animals from the saddle. But since they also study stable management before planting their feet in the stirrups, employment after graduation usually is n't a problem. The school has a 40-page list of stables looking for help. `` These are people who write or call in orders and say, ` I need a groom or an exercise rider,' `` said the 43-year-old Ms. <PERSON> Schulte </PERSON>, who started the school in 1979. The 68-acre complex has two training tracks, barns, a dormitory and a classroom. Ten groups of 12 students per year take a home correspondence course before arriving for the minimum one-month course in exercise riding _ how to give racehorses their workouts _ that many students hope will lead up the ladder to a jockey's life. The state-accredited campus is an alternative to the traditional school for jockeys: the school of hard knocks. People wanting to become jockeys usually are handed a pitchfork instead of the reins and have to work their way up. `` Unless you have good connections such as parents who are trainers or who are wealthy horse owners, it's very hard to get a job at the track,'' Ms. <PERSON> Schulte </PERSON> said. `` So this gives them a good foundation of hands-on experience with thoroughbred race horses.'' <PERSON> Brad </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopp </PERSON>, 18, of <LOCATION> Kahoka </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, graduated from the school in March and was back this week to prepare for his test to get an apprentice jockey license. `` I was getting run away with quite a bit, and now I feel I can ride about anything out there ...,'' said <PERSON> Hopp </PERSON>, whose family owns thoroughbreds. `` There was my way of riding and their way or riding, and theirs was better.'' <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said the program would help her train the thoroughbreds she owns at her farm near <LOCATION> Carlisle </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. Unlike most of the students, who are in their late teens or 20s, Mrs. <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> has several grown children. Summer and fall are the busiest times at the school 50 miles north of <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, but business picks up around <LOCATION> Derby </LOCATION> time. This year's <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Derby </ORGANIZATION> is set for Saturday. `` Many of the foreign students come especially for the <LOCATION> Derby </LOCATION>,'' Ms. <PERSON> Schulte </PERSON> said. `` They come from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. They've also come from the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. They're wanting to learn about <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> ways of training race horses and riding, and about American racetracks.'' The school has 50 horses graded in riding difficulty from `` the ones you could put your grandma on, to the real hair-raising horses,'' Ms. <PERSON> Schulte </PERSON> said. The only thing harder to handle than an out-of-control horse might be a class of junior high school students, the former teacher said. `` Get you about 30 of them and put -LRB- the students -RRB- in a situation where they do n't want to be,'' she said. `` After that, thoroughbreds are a challenge, but a pleasure.''
