<FIRST>u w AM-CleanAir 1stLd-Writethru a0644 05-03 0942</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Clean Air, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0644,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Cities Failed to Meet Ozone Standards Last Year</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 3, ``Twenty cities,'' with estimate of 135 million
people; INSERTS grafs 13-14, `Sen. George ... Air Act,'' with
comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More areas have failed to meet federal clean air standards for ozone, a major component of smog, but carbon monoxide pollution has cleared up slightly, the <ORGANIZATION> Evironmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s annual list of areas violating national clean air standards for the two pollutants shows 68 cities not meeting the ozone goals last year, an increase of six from the year before, and 59 out of compliance for carbon monoxide, a decrease of six. Twenty cities appeared on both lists, so 107 cities and rural areas containing 135 million people, according to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION>, violate one standard or both. The 24 largest metropolitan areas were on one or both lists, leaving <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> the largest area in compliance. Both pollutants are influenced by the weather, and for that reason <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> uses more than a year's data in judging compliance _ three years for ozone and two years for carbon monoxide. The ozone tabulations cover the years 1985-87 and the carbon monoxide 1986-87. If, for example, only 1986 data had been used, 50 cities would have flunked the carbon monoxide test. If 1987 readings alone had been used, 37 cities would have failed. But to be in compliance, a city must make the cut both years. The influence of weather on ozone is more pronounced. <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, Grand Rapids, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, are listed as violators this year, but not last year. All four were on the 1986 list using 1983-1985 data. The relevant ozone readings for those four areas for 1985-1987 are similar to those for 1983-1985, possibly because their summers were similar in 1983 and 1987, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> said. `` We had a hot, dry summer in the East, which tends to push up ozone levels,'' <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> said. `` It was much like the summer of 1983, except confined to the East.'' This year's lists are perhaps more important than most because <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will use them in deciding if and how to revise the Clean Air Act. While revisions are being considered, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> barred <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> from imposing penalties on any non-complying areas before Aug. 31. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> contends that it may not impose penalties for sheer failure to meet numerical standards, but must do so for areas that fail to work toward compliance. Penalties for at least 14 areas were held up by the congressional action. Those penalties can be the suspension of federal highway, sewer and air pollution program aid. Aug. 31 is now the deadline for complying with the standards, which no one expects or believes possible for many cities. Various proposals in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would extend the deadlines according to the severity of pollution and efforts needed to clean it up. Sen. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, sponsor of one bill that has cleared the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said in a statement the new report `` demonstrates that the ozone nonattainment problem continues to worsen'' and that his bill is needed. He was echoed by <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayres </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION>, a grouping of environmental and other organizations, who said the new data `` confirm that we are no longer winning the battle against air pollution and we need a revitalized Clean Air Act.'' Carbon monoxide interferes with the oxygen-carrying capacity of the blood. Ozone, the major component of smog, worsens breathing problems. Motor vehicles are involved in producing both pollutants. Carbon monoxide is emitted directly in the exhaust. As cars built before 1981, when the latest emission standards took effect, are retired, urban air should get cleaner regardless of the weather. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> says average carbon monoxide concentrations have been improving by about 4 percent a year since the mid-1970s. The agency expects all but a handful of cities _ four to six, according to <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> _ eventually to meet clean air standards for carbon monoxide without special effort. Ozone compliance is more difficult, in part because it is not emitted in exhaust. Ozone is formed by chemical reactions in sunlight between oxides of nitrogen _ still another pollutant emitted by all fossil fuel combustion, including vehicle fuels _ and volatile compounds like gasoline vapor, both from tailpipes and from normal evaporation in fuel systems. These reactions can proceed downwind of the source of the raw materials, which accounts for the presence of several rural counties, five of them in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, on the ozone non-compliance list. Ozone raw materials for the <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> counties were emitted somewhere upwind in the <LOCATION> Boston-Washington </LOCATION> corridor. Though many areas will improve as old cars are junked, far more will remain out of compliance than will be true for carbon monoxide, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> believes. Some 25 or more cities will be unable to comply with tighter controls on stationary sources of other, non-gasoline compounds like solvents, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> says. By a wide margin, the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> area is again worst for ozone pollution, in part because of the mountains around the city that keep polluted air from moving away. The area has peak ozone concentrations nearly three times the standard and an estimated 143 days of violation per year. The second worst city is <LOCATION> Bakersfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, with peaks 50 percent above the standard and 35 days of violations per year. Four other <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> cities _ <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fresno </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Modesto </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Visalia </LOCATION> _ have more than 10 days above the standard. Outside of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, only <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> have more than 10 days of violation per year.
</TEXT>
