<FIRST>r w AM-Trade     05-03 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trade,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Move to Erase Alaska Oil Curbs in Trade Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrats moved to erase the trade bill's curbs on <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> oil exports Tuesday even before the measure reached President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s desk and a threatened presidential veto House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said the move was designed to offer <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> a compromise and thus perhaps avert a veto of the 1,000-page bill which won final approval from the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> last week. Republicans countered that the real reason was to win over the votes of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> senators for a veto override. The move to drop the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> provision was contained in a resolution authorizing technical corrections in the bill. The bill cleared the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> last week by a vote of 63-36 last week _ three short of the number needed to override <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s threatened veto The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> is expected to take up the resolution this week and senators will deal with it next week when they return from a recess. One of the curbs would enable <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> to export 50,000 barrels of crude a day to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> but would require that the oil be transported to a <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> port first in American vessels. The provision is a favorite of politically influential maritime unions, and a similar feature is contained in the current U.S.-Canada free trade agreement. The other provision would limit exports from new refineries to 70,000 barrels a day and half of total production. At a news conference, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> portrayed the move as designed to keep the trade bill from going down the drain through a <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> veto. The president has been concerned about a provision that would require all but the smallest employers to give 6