<FIRST>r a AM-SexGene     05-03 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sex Gene,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Find Details of Hormone-Related Gene</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEG REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHAPEL HILL, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists have identified details of a key part of a gene responsible for male sexual development, a step that could eventually help doctors treat prostate cancer and diagnose infertility in men. The gene allows body cells to create surface structures called receptors, to which male sex hormones attach themselves. That binding triggers sex-related functions in the cells, said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> French </PERSON>, head of the laboratories of reproductive biology at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Chapel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. `` It's like a switch,'' French said. `` When the switch is turned on, it causes genes to stimulate certain characteristic functions of the cell.'' The work, reported last month in the journal Science, was carried out by French and colleagues at the university. The finding is `` a very major discovery _ it's like getting the rest of the words to ` Hamlet','' said <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Coffey </PERSON>, director of research at the <ORGANIZATION> Brady </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Johns </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hopkins </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> and chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>'s prostate cancer program. The <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> researchers used the information to create special proteins called antibodies, which detected the presence of the sex hormone receptors in laboratory animals. A test based on these antibodies may one day help doctors choose proper therapy for prostate cancer, French said. The test, called an androgen receptor assay, would tell whether prostate cells still have the receptor on their surfaces. The receptor disappears in advanced cases of prostate cancer, French said. Once the receptor is gone, hormone therapy to fight inoperable prostate cancer would be useless, said <PERSON> Coffey </PERSON>. `` We'll know not to waste time with hormone therapy if it's not going to work,'' <PERSON> Coffey </PERSON> said. Prostate cancer is the second leading cause of cancer death in men. An estimated 96,000 men get it each year in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and 27,000 die from it, according to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. The receptor test also may ultimately prove helpful in determining the cause of infertility in some men, French said. Without the receptor, a man would appear female because his cells would not respond to male sex hormone, French said. However, in some men, the receptor is present but its binding ability is impaired _ resulting in normal development but infertility.
