<HEAD>Writer Criticizes Post-War Development, Blames Stalin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A prominent writer said Tuesday the Soviets are still blaming the devastation of World War II for their poor performance in agriculture and industry, while <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> have rebuilt and prospered. <PERSON> Chingiz </PERSON> <PERSON> Aitmatov </PERSON> wrote in the government newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has fared worse than the vanquished nations in postwar economic recovery. He said dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> began the practice of ignoring the real causes of slow development and blaming it on the war. More than 20 million Soviet citizens died in the war and about one-quarter of the housing and industry in the European part of the country was destroyed. <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> launched a rebuilding campaign that replaced many factories wrecked in the war, but housing remains a serious problem and farms still fail to produce enough food for the country. `` Sometimes it is necessary to compare how quickly and powerfully has been the economic rebirth of the capitulated nations <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, which were brought to ruins, thoroughly destroyed, dismantled to the last nut,'' <PERSON> Aitmatov </PERSON> wrote. He said Soviet officials also remain reluctant to credit the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> for their help in winning the war. <PERSON> Aitmatov </PERSON> specifically mentioned nearly 15,000 warplanes provided to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Aitmatov </PERSON> is a severe critic of totalitarianism and the dehumanizing influences of Stalinism. He condemned the collectivization of the 1930s that removed peasants from the land and noted that, half a century later, the government must buy grain abroad. Soviet planners should take a lesson from reforms carried out in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, where `` no one is particularly sad about the failure of communes,'' he said. <PERSON> Aitmatov </PERSON>'s point seemed to be that more family farms would improve output. Embracing the reforms of Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, he said more democracy and openness were the only hope for a better future.
