<FIRST>r w AM-SovietJewry     05-03 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Jewry,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Now Processing Exit Applications `Reasonably Fast'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet authorities are now processing emigration applications `` reasonably fast'' and Jews who wish to leave should take advantage of the opportunity in case the situation changes, a high-ranking <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said Tuesday. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Schifter </PERSON>, assistant secretary of state for human rights and humanitarian affairs, also said he saw some signs of growing religious toleration in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Schifter </PERSON>, in remarks to the National Conference on Soviet Jewry, said he believed a huge percentage of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s two million Jews would emigrate if given the chance. Most have not applied, knowing they would be subject to discrimination in employment and other opportunities during the long _ often unending _ period while waiting for approval. <PERSON> Schifter </PERSON> said, however, `` It looks as if a good many people could get their cases processed reasonably fast if they were to apply right now. They're afraid and they're afraid quite rightfully because anything can turn in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> with a very short time and they can find themselves in great difficulty after that. `` A good many of them also are not fully aware today of what the possibilities are: that you can indeed fill out the forms, get them filed and there's a chance within six weeks or two months perhaps to get your application processed,'' he said. <PERSON> Schifter </PERSON> said Soviet Jews should be assured `` that the possibilities are there now and they ought to take advantage of it if this is what they want to do.'' After reaching a high point of 51,320 exit permits in 1979, Soviet emigration declined to 914 in 1986. It rebounded to 8,155 in 1987 and will go even higher this year if the monthly figures hold up. In March, for example, 986 Jews emigrated, the highest monthly total since 1981, according to the Conference on Soviet Jewry. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been urging the Soviets to allow freer emigration and religious freedom. <PERSON> Schifter </PERSON> said a pledge by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> last week to show more tolerance toward religion represented `` somewhat of an opening.'' He also said it appeared that for the past half year the Soviets have not enforced laws prohibiting adult Jewish education classes. <PERSON> Schifter </PERSON> expressed some optimism that the Soviets will permit the importation of bibles. <PERSON> Schifter </PERSON> did not appear particularly concerned about <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s condemnation, during a visit by Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> last month, of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's continued criticism of Soviet human rights practices `` He gets annoyed about these things,'' <PERSON> Schifter </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. `` He is a person who has a short fuse on matters of this kind. But the fact of the matter is that they are moving in this area.'' President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is expected to continue raising the issues when he goes to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> for the May 29-June 2 summit. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> told the Soviet Jewry conference that during his visit to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in April, he raised several human rights concerns, but concentrated on Jewish emigration. He said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is seeking improvements on five aspects of the issue: _ Processing time `` There are too many bureaucratic delays,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said of the application process. `` While they ca n't admit it they -LRB- Soviet leaders -RRB- see it as a real problem.'' _ Applications denied for security reasons Many Jews' applications are rejected on grounds they hold state secrets, even those who have n't worked in defense plants for decades There's been no movement from the Soviets on this, `` but at least the problem is up there on the table,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said _ Family restrictions The Soviets deny applications to those who do not have close relatives in the West, a practice that violates human rights accords the Soviets have signed, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. _ Ill applicants The Soviets should loosen up on applications from people seeking medical care elsewhere, the secretary said. _ Parental veto Under Soviet law, the parents of an applicant can veto the granting of a permit, even if the child is an adult. `` They're looking into it,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
