<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 East German Jews on Tuesday accused their departing American rabbi of high living and improper performance of duties and said they were looking for another man to become the communist nation's only rabbi. One local Jew, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said some community members had begun calling <PERSON> Isaac </PERSON> <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON> `` the <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> rabbi.'' Numerous telephone calls to <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON>'s home were unanswered Tuesday. However, <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON> said on Sunday that such issues as his apartment and car were not part of the tensions that prompted him to decide to leave. A statement from the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Jewish community, carried by the official <ORGANIZATION> ADN </ORGANIZATION> news agency, responded to criticisms made by <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON> when he announced last weekend he was leaving May 16 after only eight months. The 65-year-old rabbi from <LOCATION> Champaign </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, had complained of what he called anti-Semitism in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and interference in his work from local Jewish leadership. Tuesday's statement from local Jewish leaders said, `` His current assertion that anti-Semitic tendencies in the press ... have caused his return were never raised in his discussions with the community.'' <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> officially maintains it has wiped out anti-Semitism in its nearly four decades of existence. The statement also charged <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON> with improperly carrying out some of his duties, such as dealing with the elderly and preparing youths for Bar Mitzvah. The Polish-born <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON>, a Nazi prisoner during World War II, in September became the first rabbi in 21 years for this nation's Jewish community of about 450 people There was no official word on a replacement for <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON>. Community members who spoke on condition of anonymity said <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON> would be succeeded by <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> Rabbi <PERSON> Ernst </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorge </PERSON>. Others sources close to the community said <PERSON> Lorge </PERSON> would be appointed only on an interim basis, while a young rabbi was sought as a permanent replacement. <PERSON> Lorge </PERSON>, 71, said Tuesday in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> he had received no official invitation to come to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` If I do, I would have to think about it,'' he said. He said he did not want to stay in East Germay year-round but might accept a short-term arrangement. <PERSON> Lorge </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> Mainz </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, and emigrated to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> fleeing Nazi persecution in 1936. <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON>, explaining his reasons for leaving in an interview Tuesday, said, `` I am unhappy about <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and anti-Semitism.'' He criticized the East German news media's depiction of Palestinian unrest in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` Sometimes the way <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> is depicted is in a Nazi-like fashion,'' he said. `` They have cut anti-Semitism but have not succeeded in uprooting it.'' He also complained about interference in his work. His main objections focused on the local Jewish community president, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirchner </PERSON>, who signed the statement distributed Tuesday by the East German news agency. `` The assertion that Rabbi <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON> was hindered in carrying out his functions by members, or the community representatives, or other people must be rejected with emphasis,'' the statement said. <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Jewish community members, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said there had long been criticism of <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON> and his lifestyle. `` He would drive to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> every day to get fresh tomatoes,'' said one local Jew. Community members said <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON> was provided with a large apartment and a car during his tenure. The community supported <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON> with funds provided by the government. The East German Jewish community includes less than 350 officially registered members and about 100 other worshipers, <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON> said. However, some estimates say that there are as many as 2,500 non-practicing Jews in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>.
