<HEAD>Markey Urges NRC To Reject Rules Change for Seabrook Low-Power
License</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A congressional critic of nuclear power urged the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday to reject a staff proposal that would permit atomic reactors to operate at low power without an alarm system to warn nearby residents in case of an emergency. The recommendation, scheduled for a preliminary commission vote shortly, is aimed at the <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>, plant. The Atomic Safety and <ORGANIZATION> Licensing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> has blocked a low-power license for <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> because of the lack of a warning system for neighboring communities in nearby <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. `` During fuel loading and low-power operation, the potential for an accident still exists, including the possibility of a reactor reaching a critical level,'' Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., said in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lando </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> `` While the magnitude of the risk may be lower -LRB- than at full power -RRB-, it is no lower than it was in 1982 when the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> examined the issue in detail and adopted existing standards,'' <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> wrote Critics say <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> officials want to quickly secure a low-power license because they fear they will lose their chance to operate the $ 5.4 billion plant if <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is elected president. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has led the fight against <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> and his refusal to cooperate in emergency evacuation planning for the six <ORGANIZATION> Bay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZ