<HEAD>Court Of Appeals Reinstates Lawsuit Against Tobacco Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A widow whose husband smoked and died of lung cancer can pursue a wrongful death lawsuit against a tobacco company and a retailer that sold cigarettes, the <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled Tuesday. A three-judge panel unanimously overturned a district court ruling in May 1987 that <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Forster </PERSON>'s claim was pre-empted by the Federal Cigarette and Advertising Act. In March 1985, Mrs. <PERSON> Forster </PERSON> and her husband, <PERSON> John </PERSON>, sued <ORGANIZATION> R.J. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, manufacturers of Camel cigarettes, and <ORGANIZATION> Erickson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, owner of <ORGANIZATION> Holiday </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>. The Forsters claimed the retailer sold <PERSON> Forster </PERSON> the cigarettes. <PERSON> Forster </PERSON>, who was diagnosed as having inoperable lung cancer in November 1984, died of the disease in June 1985, and the suit, originally filed as a product liability case, was amended to a wrongful death action. The lawsuit alleges that cigarettes caused the lung cancer. Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Kalitowski </PERSON>, who wrote the majority opinion, said the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> historically has taken a narrow view of federal pre-emption. In overturning the lower court, <PERSON> Kalitowski </PERSON> said: `` Our holding is founded on the strong presumption, basic to our system of federalism, that state police powers are not superseded by federal actions'' without `` clear and unmistakable congressional intent or absolute necessity.'' `` We recognize appellants' claims may be difficult to prove,'' the ruling said. `` However, the difficulty of proof should not preclude the basic right to present claims.''
