<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House on Tuesday urged President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to maintain at least 20 missile-firing submarines as part of any U.S.-Soviet agreement to cut back strategic nuclear weapons. The voice-vote decision came as the chamber adopted an amendment to a bill authorizing the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget for the fiscal year starting Oct. 1. Both nations are now negotiating to achieve a Strategic Arms Reduction Talks -LRB- START -RRB- treaty that could provide reductions of up to 50 percent in each country's stockpile of long-range atomic weapons. Those stockpiles are made up of submarine-launched missiles, land-based missiles and bombers. Under the proposed treaty, both sides would be required to reduce and restructure their arsenals. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> now has more than half its strategic firepower aboard 36 missile-firing subs, including 28 Poseidon-class boats and eight of the giant Trident-class subs. Seven more Tridents are under construction, while a 16th is authorized in the bill now on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has n't yet decided how to restack its stockpile under a START treaty, but the amendment offered by Rep. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, said at least 20 submarines should be retained. `` Our ability to prevent nuclear war depends more than anything else on the maintenance of a survivable nuclear deterrent,'' said <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON>, who added that subs are virtually invulnerable to attack while they are at sea. `` It is in our interest to have the maximum number of submarines possible,'' <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON> said. As it worked through the bill, the chamber also gave voice vote approval to an amendment banning the sending of any <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> vessels to help the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> patrol the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. Supporters of the amendment had said a day earlier they planned to drop the proposal in the wake of a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> announcement that the deployment plan was being shelved. But as the issue arose Tuesday, a procedural snare meant it was easier to simply approve the amendment than to bypass it. In another decision, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted 213-195 to give federal contractors more freedom to set pay scales. The vote approved an amendment overhauling the Davis-Bacon Act, the 1931 law which requires that employees covered by contracts on federal jobs worth more than $ 2,000 should be paid the prevailing local wage rate, a figure determined by the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The rate is commonly the same rate paid union workers. The measure approved Tuesday would raise the threshold figure from $ 2,000 to $ 50,000. The vote came shortly before the chamber rejected, 210-204, a move that would have raised the Davis-Bacon threshold from $ 2,000 to $ 250,000. The Davis-Bacon law was enacted during the Great Depression amid worries that construction companies would hire cheap labor. Tuesday's votes on the bill went generally along party lines, with <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> backing the $ 50,000 threshold and Republicans supporting the $ 250,000 threshold. There have been a number of attempts during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration to change the law by critics who contend that the $ 2,000 figure is outdated. Organized labor has strongly supported the Davis-Bacon law. The amendment approved Tuesday was essentially the same measure passed last Aug. 4 by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. That bill has n't yet come to the floor, but committee leaders said they offered it as an amendment to the Pentagon budget bill in an effort to forestall the amendment proposing a $ 250,000 threshold. Neither the START nor the Davis-Bacon amendments adopted Tuesday is part of the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget bill which the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> will be considering next week. Differences between the measures that eventually pass each chamber will be worked out in a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> conference committee. Both measures authorize $ 299.5 billion in <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spending for the next fiscal year.
