<BYLINE>By PETER SHINKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man convicted of murdering seven women and letting their bodies rot faces life in prison rather than death under an unusual sentence handed down Tuesday. Common Pleas Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Latrone </PERSON> issued six death sentences against <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> `` Marty'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> but ordered him first to serve up to 14 years in prison on seven counts of abuse of a corpse and life in prison for the remaining murder. Latrone, who ordered the sentences to run consecutively, explained that he chose life in prison over the death penalty on the first murder count because of a mitigating circumstance _ the lack of a previous record. But the conviction on the first count legally qualified as an aggravating circumstance on the second through seventh murder counts, necessitating the death penalty in those six cases. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> could not apply for parole during the life sentence, however, without putting the death sentence into effect, defense attorney <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Moldovsky </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, whose attorney said he was mentally retarded, sat motionlessly through the sentencing, a half-smoked cigarette tucked behind his ear. <PERSON> Moldovsky </PERSON> called the sentence `` unusually compassionate and brilliant.'' But Assistant District Attorney <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, who characterized <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> as a `` serial killer'' during the trial, questioned the legality of the order. `` It would appear that the greater sentence would come first,'' he said, meaning the death penalty. The <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> reviews all death sentences. Last week, Latrone convicted <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> of seven counts of murder and abuse of a corpse. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> waived his right to a jury trial, leaving the decisions, including sentencing, solely to the judge. Police found the bodies of seven women in August 1987, after <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> was evicted from his apartment because of a putrid stench. Officers found six rotting bodies in <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>'s bedroom, leg and foot bones outside his apartment and a torso in a neighboring house's basement At his mother's urging, <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> surrendered to police a week after the bodies were discovered. In a statement his lawyer unsuccessfully contested, <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> told police he strangled the women while having sex and after feeding them drugs and alcohol. He said that when the bodies began piling up in his apartment, he began experiencing trouble with `` fur-ball bugs,'' or maggots, and with birds feeding on the remains outside the window. The 28-year-old <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> did not testify during the six-week trial. <PERSON> Moldovsky </PERSON>, who had argued his client did not know right from wrong and might have killed the women accidentally or because of drug or alcohol use, said he would consult with <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>'s family before deciding whether to appeal.
