<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The city elections board voted unanimously Tuesday to hold a special mayoral election in spring 1989 to choose a successor to the late Mayor <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>, whose term would have ended in 1991. `` We're proceeding with the 1989 election unless we're ordered to the contrary by the court,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Leach </PERSON>, a spokesman for the city <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elections </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commissioners </ORGANIZATION>. The board had voted April 24 to hold a special mayoral election in April 1989 if City Clerk <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Kozubowski </PERSON> declared that <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s death in late November created a vacancy in the position. <PERSON> Kozubowski </PERSON> said at the time he would n't issue such a declaration unless ordered to do so by a court. But on Monday, he apparently changed his mind and provided the elections board with the documentation, <PERSON> Leach </PERSON> said. `` The board decided to accept the declaration of a vacancy from the city clerk and decided to go ahead with the 1989 election unless we're ordered not to by the courts,'' <PERSON> Leach </PERSON> said. Circuit Judge <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Wachowski </PERSON> said last week he expected to rule on the issue at a hearing Friday. Supporters of acting Mayor <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alderman </PERSON> <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, a rival and potential mayoral candidate, have been feuding over when the next mayoral election should be held. <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> hailed Tuesday's decision as `` a great victory for all of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>.'' `` We have never doubted that 1989 is the legally correct time for a special election,'' he said in a statement issued from <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, where he is attending a meeting of