<HEAD>Toyota Announces Program to Fix Brake Pedal Pulsation in Camrys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> announced Tuesday that owners of about 380,000 Camrys are entitled to have a brake pedal pulsation problem repaired free. The voluntary recall, which is available to owners of 1983-1986 Camrys and certain early 1987 Camrys, is designed to correct a brake pedal pulsation problem that some owners have complained about, said <PERSON> Debra </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sales </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Torrance </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. Brake pedal pulsation can be felt by drivers when their foot is on the pedal, but it does not affect braking effectiveness or steering control, <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> said. Brake pedal pulsation is caused by movement of the brake pads as they pass over the brake disc, she said. Later this month, <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> plans to notify owners of the cars in phases based on model years. The problem will be fixed at no charge to the customer for a period of 12 months from the date of notification, the company said. The action comes in the wake of a class-action lawsuit filed in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> state court by two public interest law firms seeking free repairs and reimbursement for car owners who have paid to have their Camrys fixed or checked. `` We're impressed with this step they're taking. There's no question it's a major commitment,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> of the Center for Law in the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interest </ORGANIZATION> said of <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION>'s announcement. Attorneys will pursue the suit, however, because, `` We've alleged that they've engaged in a secret warranty for this defect by notifying the dealers and not notifying the owners,'' <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> said The Center for Auto Safety in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, joined in the suit filed April 20 in <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>.
