<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sandinista police detained five hunger strike sympathizers on Tuesday when they tried to talk to reporters in the area where workers were on the ninth day of a fast to demand higher pay. The officers, members of the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Special </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> unit, cited a ban on unauthorized public activities. Police have taken at least 40 people into custody during the past week in connection with the hunger strike by more than 30 construction workers and car mechanics. Sandinista policewomen, wearing black berets and toting rubber truncheons, cordoned off the front of the headquarters of the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, a coalition of socialist anti-government unions, and kept journalists away. The five sympathizers stood around the corner from the union hall and told reporters that authorities would not let them get close to the union building, where some hunger strikers peered through locked gates. Police pushed through the journalists, grabbed the five and shoved them into three different vehicles. `` This is an unauthorized public act,'' said a Sandinista police officer who refused to give his name. Police last Friday night permitted a group of <LOCATION> Sandinsta </LOCATION> students to hold a rally at the same spot where the arrests were made. Interior Minister <PERSON> Tomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Borge </PERSON> last week reportedly punched in the mouth the director of an anti-government radio station for broadcasting what <PERSON> Borge </PERSON> said was wrong information about the strike. The Sandinista newspaper Barricada reported the altercation. About 1,500 construction workers and auto mechanics have been on strike since the end of February for higher salaries and improved working conditions. The wildcat strikes are an embarrassment to the leftist Sandinista government. Such strikes were illegal for almost six years under a state of emergency that was lifted in January. President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> removed the restrictions as part of a regional peace plan which includes calls for democratic reforms. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> and the presidents of <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> signed the agreement last August. Public demonstrations are allowed only with <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> permission. The state-run telephone company meanwhile cut off service to about 6,000 offices and homes in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> because of overdue bills totaling $ 1.8 million. The cutoff left the national banking system, embassies, state-run enterprises, government offices and thousands of homes in the capital without telephone service. There are a total of 29,000 phones in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>, a city of about 900,000 people. Hundreds of Nicaraguans went to the <ORGANIZATION> Nicaraguan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecommunications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> protesting the shutoff and saying they had paid their bills. A telephone company spokeswoman, <PERSON> Maritza </PERSON> <PERSON> Flores </PERSON>, acknowledged that some phones were disconnected because of `` computer problems,'' but said other customers had not paid their bills for several months. The cutoff came Saturday and was reported in local newspapers Tuesday.
