<FIRST>u i AM-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru   05-03 0924</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0689,0950</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strikers Demand Legalization of Solidarity; Walesa Speaks at
Shipyard</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos WAR50,51</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 6th pvs, ``A striker...'' to UPDATE
with sympathy strikes in Gdansk, march in Warsaw; picks up 7th pvs:
Walesa, who...; SUBS 19th graf pvs, ``Government and...'' with 1
graf to UPDATE with mine strike ending.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 7,000 strikers at the <LOCATION> Lenin </LOCATION> shipyard, where Solidarity was born eight years ago, demanded Tuesday that the outlawed union federation be made legal again. The government called that `` not negotiable.'' Solidarity founder <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, 44, spoke to the strikers several times, but said he would not lead the strike. `` I am not your leader. I'm tired,'' said the man who vaulted the shipyard fence in 1980 and took charge of a labor revolt that brought down a government. `` You need a new <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, many more new Walesas.'' `` You declared this strike,'' he said. `` I'm with you and I'll always be with you I can advise you. I have some experience. `` If we do n't achieve a real reform this time, then we will have a bloody revolution.'' A striker offered a loaf of bread, a Polish gesture of hospitality. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> broke off a piece and munched on it. Four thousand ship-repair workers and 1,000 port workers at another <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> shipyard stayed off the job Tuesday in sympathy with the strikers at the Lenin shipyard, said <PERSON> Joanna </PERSON> <PERSON> Wojciechowicz </PERSON>, a Solidarity activist in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>. The report could not be independently confirmed. There was no answer at the ship repair yard. In <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, meanwhile, protesters marched in the streets in support of the strikers, an opposition spokesman said. They were dispersed by police. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, who won the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize, still works at the shipyard as an electrician but is on sick leave this week, complaining of back pains and low blood sugar. On the first day of the shipyard strike Monday, workers asked that a local Solidarity chapter be approved, but on Tuesday demanded reinstatement of the union nationwide. Solidarity, the first independent union in the Soviet bloc, was crushed and outlawed after martial law was declared Dec. 13, 1981. A large poster at the gate listed the other demands: higher pay, release of political prisoners and reinstatement of fired activists. Polish workers want pay raises of up to 60 percent to compensate for price increases of 42 percent that resulted from reduction of subsidies by the Communist government. The labor trouble, which has lasted more than a week, is the worst in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> since the crackdown on Solidarity. The biggest strike is by 15,000 workers at the <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION> steel complex in the south, the nation's largest industrial plant. Government spokesman <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON> said of the demand for nationwide recognition of Solidarity: `` This is not a question that can be an object of negotiations. It is not negotiable.'' During a <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> news conference, he said strike leaders were `` professional politicians'' working for Western powers. Despite his protests, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> was emerging Tuesday as the dominant figure among the <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> strikers. `` We lost eight years,'' he said through a loudspeaker. `` Here, in the birthplace of Solidarity, I state to the authorities that they are deepening the losses, they are forcing Solidarity to lead the nation onto the road to reforms.'' In <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, strikers customarily occupy their places of work. When police cordoned off the shipyard Tuesday, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> stayed inside with the strikers, said his adviser, the Rev. <PERSON> Henryk </PERSON> <PERSON> Jankowski </PERSON>. Strikes began April 25 with a wildcat action by transit workers in <LOCATION> Bydgoszcz </LOCATION> that was settled the same day with pay raises of at least 50 percent. The <ORGANIZATION> Nowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Huta </ORGANIZATION> strike began the next day. On Friday, thousand of employees at the <ORGANIZATION> Stalowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wola </ORGANIZATION> heavy machinery plant quit working but the strike was settled Saturday by promises of higher pay. Government and opposition spokesmen confirmed a brief work stoppage Tuesday at a railroad car plant in <LOCATION> Wroclaw </LOCATION>, and opposition spokesmen said about 1,000 miners occupied a copper mine in western <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> for eight hours. <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarmuzek </PERSON>, manager of the <LOCATION> Rudna </LOCATION> mine, said only 150 workers were involved. University students in <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poznan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> struck in sympathy with the workers, according to opposition spokesmen in the three cities. Police have rounded up about a dozen dissident leaders and apparently cut off the telephones of others. Sources said some people were staying away from home for fear of detention. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> told reporters that <PERSON> Bogdan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lis </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> regional Solidarity chief, and eight other regional leaders were detained. Other prominent figures reported arrested were dissident intellectual <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> <PERSON> Michnik </PERSON> and <PERSON> Leszek </PERSON> <PERSON> Moczulski </PERSON>, leader of the rightist opposition Confederation of Independent <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Urban called the detentions `` preventive.'' The strike at the 12,000-worker Lenin shipyard began Monday soon after the breakfast break and grew to between 7,000 and 8,000 people by Tuesday morning, said <PERSON> Alojzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Szablewski </PERSON>, chairman of the strike committee. On Tuesday, the shipyard cranes were idle and only transport, power and some other essential operations appeared to be functioning. Hundreds of strikers were at the main gates, wearing Solidarity badges and arm bands. The gate was festooned with yellow flowers, Solidarity banners, and pictures of Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, a native of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, and the <PERSON> Black </PERSON> <PERSON> Madonna </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s revered icon. Some workers sat atop the gate, which bore a huge sign saying `` Occupation Strike.'' Others climbed on the roofs of buildings to hear <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> speak. Cheers of `` Solidarity!'' and `` Lech, <PERSON> Lech </PERSON>!'' rose on both sides of the gate when <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> arrived.
