<HEAD>Dukakis Hails ``Great'' Results in Indiana, Ohio</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democratic front-runner <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> refused to lay claim to the presidential nomination after primary wins Tuesday in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> but said `` it's going to be difficult'' for rival <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> to overtake him now. `` I feel great about today and the results today,'' the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor told a <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> news conference after racking up big wins in two of Tuesday's three primary contests. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> won the District of <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> primary. `` We've got to keep working,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said, reminding backers he was still more than 500 delegates short of the 2,081 needed to nominate. Despite a series of primary wins over <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said the race for the nomination is not over. He vowed to campaign aggressively through the final day of the primary season _ June 7 _ when voters in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> cast ballots. `` I think it's going to be difficult,'' he said when asked if <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> had a chance to win the fight for the nomination. Asked if he thought <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> would view the latest primary results as a trend, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> smiled and said: `` I hope so.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has been increasingly critical of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in recent days, but the governor declined to say whether he thought his rival should tone it down. `` He's going to have to make that judgment,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` I'm going to try to keep this as positive as I can. I do n't mind disagreement on issues. I just hope we can both continue to campaign with the respect we've had for each other in the past year.'' Asked whether he believed President <PERS