<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Government Ethics Office Probing Letter Sent by Meese for Japan
Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Office of Government Ethics launched an investigation Tuesday into a letter signed by Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> and sent to 30,000 people encouraging them to attend a conference in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the head of the office said Tuesday night. `` It started today,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Q. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nebeker </PERSON>, head of the ethics office. `` As a judge, I have received invitations of this sort in year's past. I do n't know at this point what this one is.'' <PERSON> Nebeker </PERSON>, a former judge on the <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, said he was not sure what the problems might be with the mailing, adding, `` We're attempting to ascertain what the facts are.'' In the letter, <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> is soliciting attendance at a meeting for which the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sponsor is a profit-making organization. The presidential order on ethics that is policed by the ethics office forbids federal officials from engaging in any conduct that might present the appearance of a conflict of interest or of losing objectivity in governmental decision making or favoritism. The appearance of such a problem is enough to trigger an investigation, even when such problems do n't exist in reality. It is a crime to use the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> seal for non-authorized purposes. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s letters on Office of the Attorney General stationery with the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> seal invited the recipients to join him at a legal and economic conference in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> on Aug. 29 to Sept. 1. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> will be heading the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegation to the conference called, `` The U.S.-Japan Bilateral Session: A New Era in Legal and Economic Relations.'' The meeting is sponsored in part by the <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ambassador </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> to </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, according to the letter. While People to <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> is a non-profit organization set up originally in the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> by then-President <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON>, the Citizen Ambassador Program is a profit-making organization, the chairman of that firm said Tuesday night. `` Yes, the Citizen Ambassador Program is for-profit, which is how <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> established the program with the intention of making it self-supporting,'' <PERSON> Norm </PERSON> <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from his home in <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> said the letter went to about 30,000 people whose names were `` provided by everyone from the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the advisory committees on both sides, to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Eastland </PERSON> said the department was unaware that a profit-making organization was involved, but he contended that even if it were, <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s involvement might still be justified due to the department's interest in international legal questions. `` People to <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> came to us and represented themselves as a non-profit, tax-exempt organization,'' <PERSON> Eastland </PERSON> said. `` To the extent that they're linked to some group that is profit-making, that was not known by those making decisions on the attorney general's participation. `` In the event it turns out a profit-making entity is involved, it could be argued that the department could engage in a joint venture so long as it was in the department's interest, and obviously we have an interest in international legal questions,'' he said. <PERSON> Eastland </PERSON> said legal and ethics authorities in the department reviewed both this letter and a similar one sent by <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> for a conference sponsored by <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> to </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> last summer in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to make sure it was all right for the attorney general to participate. The attorney general also hosted the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> delegation in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> last year. In both cases, <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s expenses will be paid by the department, he said. The two-page letter from <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> was dated April 26 and says, in part, `` Although attended and assisted by senior officials of the governments of both <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the conference is fittingly a non-governmental one administered on behalf of the Japanese by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organizations </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Keidanren </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- and on the American side by the Citizen Ambassador Program of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> to </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> organization.'' `` I invite and encourage your participation. Sincerely <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, Attorney General.'' The letter was accompanied by an engraved invitation and a response card to be sent to the Citizen Ambassador Program in <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION> which would provide details on the trip. <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> said he could not say how much profit might be involved for his firm, which is quoting participants a cost of $ 3,240, including transportation and lodging and an $ 800 registration fee set by the Japanese organizing committee. `` I wish I knew,'' he said. `` It's not large. It depends on the participation in the conference. Those profits are used to encourage further exchanges, as they have for the last 35 years.'' <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Ursula </PERSON>, was paid by <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> to </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> to go on last summer's <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> trip, <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> said. `` Her way to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> was paid last year by <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> to </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> in return for the frankly exhausting role that she fulfilled in being head of the women's contingent for the conference,'' <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> said. `` This was an economic law conference in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> which Mr. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> hosted last year and which was very much the precursor to the Japanese meeting.'' <PERSON> Eastland </PERSON> said department regulations allow for payments for spouses to be reimbursed by an outside entity, profit-making or non-profit making, if certain conditions are met. In this case, the conditions were met, he said. <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> said the cost for the <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> meeting, including transportation, was about $ 2,500. The registration fee there was $ 400. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s expenses for the <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> trip will be picked up by the government, since he is making an official visit at the invitation of the Japanese Minister of Justice, <PERSON> Yukio </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayashida </PERSON>.
