<HEAD>Conrail Announces $58 Million Settlement in Amtrak Crash Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Consolidated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday it has tentatively agreed to pay $ 58 million to families of people killed in <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION>'s worst accident, the 1987 collision of a passenger train with <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION> engines in Chase, Md. The agreement was reached with attorneys representing the estates of the victims and is subject to the approval of <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION>'s directors and various courts, according to a <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION> statement <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Holloschutz </PERSON> said he did not know how many of the victims' families the agreement covers. The $ 58 million would be in addition to the $ 7.5 million <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to place in escrow as a part of a proposed settlement with those injured in the collision, he said. <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION> said it did not concede liability for the accident in the proposed settlements. On Jan. 4, 1987, former <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION> engineer <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gates </PERSON> missed a track signal and drove three linked <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION> locomotives into the path of a 660-passenger <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> train traveling an estimated 125 mph. The accident, the worst in <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION>'s history, killed 16 people and injured more than 175. <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION> is suing to force <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> to cover payments for the passenger injuries and deaths, contending that a prior agreement required <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> to cover the payments. If that suit fails, <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION> will pursue its claims against its insurers, according to the company. <PERSON> Gates </PERSON>, who was n't injured in the accident, was sentenced earlier this year in <ORGANIZATION> Baltimore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to five years in prison after pleading guilty to manslaughter. Gates' brakeman at the time of the crash, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Cromwell </PERSON>, was granted immunity from criminal action after agreeing to help prosecutors. <PERSON> Gates </PERSON>, an acknowledged alcoholic, has admitted smoking marijuana on the train but the court ruled that it could not determine if he was under the influence of the drug at the time of the accident. <PERSON> Gates </PERSON> also faces charges in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Court in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> for conspiracy, obstruction of an agency investigation, and lying to investigators from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> about drug use.
