<HEAD>Attorneys Make Final Arguments In Polygamist Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf to UPDATE that jury deliberations not expected
until sometime Wednesday.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Religious beliefs do not excuse four polygamist clan members from blame for a church bombing and standoff with police that they claim were mandated by God, a prosecutor said Tuesday. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lambert </PERSON>, in closing arguments capping the federal trial of the four defendants, admonished jurors not to ask themselves what they would do if they felt divinely inspired to break the law. `` There is no revelation exception to the laws of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' he said. <PERSON> Lambert </PERSON> was among a trio of prosecutors wrapping up their cases against clan matriarch <PERSON> Vickie </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>; her son-in-law, <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>; <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>'s brother, <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>; and Mrs. Singer's son, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>. They are charged in the Jan. 16 bombing of the <ORGANIZATION> Mormon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Kamas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> and an ensuing 13-day standoff at their Marion farm. The prosecutors were followed by summations from defense attorneys. After instructions from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, the jury was expected to begin deliberating sometime Wednesday. Clan members have said they believe <PERSON> God </PERSON> ordered the bombing as a sign of the impending collapse of church, state and nation, and that he guided them through the siege. The standoff ended in a shootout that killed state Corrections Lt. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> House </PERSON> and wounded <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Brent </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said Mrs. Singer, 45, was as much a part of the bombing as <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>, who admitted on the witness stand that he planted the dynamite. He was the only one of the four defendants to testify. While conceding that Mrs. Singer never actually took part in the bombing, <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> contended that she aided <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>, making her `` just as guilty of committing that crime herself.'' `` They were just waiting for the day. This was the biggest thing in their lives since <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON> pulled a gun on lawmen several years ago,'' <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said. The prosecutor's reference to <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>, the slain polygamist husband of Mrs. Singer, drew hard stares from his widow. Singer was gunned down in 1979 at the same farm by lawmen serving arrest warrants stemming from his refusal to send his children to public schools. However, Mrs. <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Kathyrn </PERSON> <PERSON> Collard </PERSON>, countered that prosecutors had `` simply no evidence that <PERSON> Vickie </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON> committed any of these crimes that she is accused of.'' <PERSON> Collard </PERSON> said Mrs. Singer consistently stated that during the standoff, she would simply pray and `` trust in the Lord ... Hardly the words of a hardened criminal bent on killing <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents.'' <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> cited Mrs. Singer's telephone statements to an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> hostage negotiator and a reporter the day of the bombing. He also referred to her diary and `` prayer cards'' which asked for a divine blessing on the 87 sticks of dynamite. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwendiman </PERSON> focused on the attempted murder and assault charges, devoting much of his time to evidence against <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>, 21. <PERSON> Schwendiman </PERSON> argued that Singer decided to kill lawmen when he took aim at the doorway of a nearby building where a six-man <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> team, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and another dog handler had secretly hidden themselves the night before. Five bullets from Singer's .30 - caliber carbine, including the slug that killed <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, were found embedded in the doorway and walls of the building, <PERSON> Schwendiman </PERSON> State authorities have said they will file murder charges after the federal trial is over. The federal indictment charged the defendants with maliciously damaging the church building with an explosive device; use of a bomb; attempted murder of federal agents; assaulting, resisting and impeding federal officers; possession of a bomb; possession of a sawed-off shotgun; and use of a firearm linked to the charges involving the federal agents. Mrs. Singer is charged with all counts, while <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON> faces all but the shotgun-posession charge. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON> both are charged with the assault, attempted murder and firearms violations. Charges against two other family members _ who are both daughters of Mrs. Singer and wives of <LOCATION> Addam </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Swapp </LOCATION> _ were dropped. In his defense summation, <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, told jurors that his client had expected a violent confrontation from authorities following the bombing, but he did n't plan one. <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> also said the testimony of <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents about the shootout contained inconsitencies.
