<HEAD>Johnny Carson Says `Tonight Show' To Resume Production</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` The Tonight Show'' will resume production May 11 with <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> writing his own material after talks with striking scriptwriters failed, the entertainer said Tuesday. <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> is believed to be the first independent producer to defy the strike by the <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, which began March 7. He will write his opening monologue and guest introductions, with no striking writers returning to work, his statement said. <PERSON> Carson </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Hookstratten </PERSON>, said he was `` stupefied by the <ORGANIZATION> WGA </ORGANIZATION>'s apparent lack of desire to negotiate in good faith.'' <ORGANIZATION> WGA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON> said Tuesday that union negotiators talked with <PERSON> Carson </PERSON>'s production company earlier in the day and added that, `` We are ready and willing to continue to negotiate in good faith.'' Because <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> is not a guild member, he would not violate the strike by writing his own material, Ms. <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON> said. In his statement, <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> said he had `` exhausted every possibility of reaching an agreement'' and was concerned about his show's staff. `` There are numerous ` Tonight Show' staff members, many have been with us for over 20 years, who are in danger of losing their jobs if this strike goes on much longer. I ca n't let that happen. I also ca n't turn my back on the ` Tonight Show' audience, who've remained loyal these past 25 years It's time to go back to work.'' <PERSON> Brandon </PERSON> <PERSON> Tartikoff </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION>, welcomed <PERSON> Carson </PERSON>'s decision. The network has been airing reruns during the strike. `` TV and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> are not the same without him,'' <PERSON> Tartikoff </PERSON> said. Ms. <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Carson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tonight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the entertainer's production company, had met with the guild six times since March 23, with the last formal session on April 28 The company has been seeking a waiver from the strike or an independent agreement with the guild. <PERSON> Hookstratten </PERSON> said the production company had agreed to nearly all of the union's contract conditions before the guild informed <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> last week that it would not ratify any independent contracts until at least 10 percent of its 9,000 members had been offered jobs by independent producers. The guild has approved only two independent contracts so far, with the `` New Smothers Brothers Comedy Hour'' and <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Reitman </PERSON> Productions, makers of the movie `` Ghostbusters.'' The main issues in the writers' strike against television and movie producers are payment for foreign broadcasts and reruns and the writers' degree of creative control they have over their work. There have been no formal negotiations since mediated talks broke off March 10.
