<HEAD>`Caine Mutiny' Film Inspired by Iran-Contra Hearings</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Altman </PERSON> almost declined to direct the television version of `` The Caine Mutiny Court-Martial,'' until he realized how many people were glued to their TV sets every day for the Iran-Contra hearings. `` I thought, if I can do the same thing, maybe they've trained an audience for me,'' <PERSON> Altman </PERSON> said. Trained or not, audiences seeking fine drama will do well to catch `` The Caine Mutiny Court-Martial'' Sunday on CBS. The play is still riveting, <PERSON> Altman </PERSON>'s direction is poetic, and the performances by his distinguished young cast are superb all the way around. <PERSON> Altman </PERSON>, best-known for his feature films -LRB- `` M-A-S-H,'' `` <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>'' -RRB- and a veteran of filming stage works -LRB- `` Streamers,'' `` Come Back to the 5 & amp; Dime, <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Dean </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Dean </PERSON>'' -RRB-, said he at first had no interest in the project because of the 1954 <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Dmytryk </PERSON> film classic `` The Caine Mutiny,'' which starred <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Bogart </PERSON> as quintessential petty tyrant Capt. <PERSON> Queeg </PERSON>. This is not a remake of the movie, but rather the Broadway play <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Wouk </PERSON> adapted from his Pulitzer Prize-winning novel. The movie was based on the entire novel. The play is just the court-martial, the dramatic core of the book. <PERSON> Altman </PERSON>, who co-produced the piece, intentionally cast a younger <PERSON> Queeg </PERSON> than audiences who remember <PERSON> Bogart </PERSON> will expect, <PERSON> Brad </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> -LRB- `` Midnight Express'' -RRB-. `` <PERSON> Queeg </PERSON> was 37 years old in that book, and <PERSON> Brad </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> is 38,'' said <PERSON> Altman </PERSON>. `` I tried to bring all those ages down to what was real.'' It was a wise move. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> makes the role his own. <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Bogosian </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> actor and playwright -LRB- `` Talk Radio'' -RRB-, will be new to most viewers, though he's done guest shots on such network shows as `` Crime Story'' and `` Miami Vice.'' He's excellent as Lt. <PERSON> Greenwald </PERSON>, the reluctant defense attorney. <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> plays Lt. <PERSON> Maryk </PERSON>, the not-too-bright young officer on trial for mutiny for relieving <PERSON> Queeg </PERSON> of command in a typhoon. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallagher </PERSON> -LRB- `` The Murder of <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Phagan </PERSON>'' -RRB- plays Lt. Cmdr. Challee, the prosecutor who gets more than he bargained for. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> has a small but meaty role as Lt. <PERSON> Keefer </PERSON>, the non-committal witness who turns out to be a pivotal character in the drama. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, who stars in the <ORGANIZATION> HBO </ORGANIZATION> series <PERSON> Altman </PERSON> is directing, `` <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON>'88,'' plays Capt. <PERSON> Blakely </PERSON>, the judge. `` The tragic figure in that case to me was Challee,'' said <PERSON> Altman </PERSON>. `` He's the guy who felt betrayed.'' As the court-martial opens, <PERSON> Challee </PERSON> is so sure of his case against <PERSON> Maryk </PERSON>, he has talked his friend, <PERSON> Greenwald </PERSON>, into serving as defense attorney. At first <PERSON> Greenwald </PERSON> is contemptuous of his own client and seems almost negligent in his defense. But <PERSON> Greenwald </PERSON> wants to win, and as the court-martial progresses, he takes his distasteful task to heart, expertly baiting <PERSON> Queeg </PERSON> until the captain breaks down on the stand before the shocked but sympathetic court-martial. <PERSON> Altman </PERSON> did n't get much of an audience for his first network TV projects, the <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinter </PERSON> plays `` The Dumbwaiter'' and `` The Room'' for <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>. `` The Caine Mutiny Court-Martial'' is a lot more accessible to a large audience. As evidenced by viewer interest in the Iran-Contra and <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> hearings and the success of television shows about lawyers, there's a natural drama to the courtroom setting. <PERSON> Altman </PERSON> enhances <PERSON> Wouk </PERSON>'s piece with a unique brand of realism. The camera roams around the courtroom like an eye, picking up details here and there, like <PERSON> Queeg </PERSON>'s incessant clicking of two steel ball bearings to calm his nerves. True to the <PERSON> Altman </PERSON> style, characters talk over each other in asides that ca n't quite be made out, until a conversation finally predominates. In the first half of the drama, a band practices outside on the parade field, providing patriotic background music for the prosecution's case. When the defense takes over the next day, it is raining. In an especially poetic moment, after <PERSON> Queeg </PERSON> has been excused from the stand, <PERSON> Altman </PERSON>'s camera stays on him in a very long shot as he leaves the far end of the building, a lost and broken man. `` I think at the end after it's all over there'll be a lot of that, ` What was that? Who's the bad guy?' That's what I want,'' said <PERSON> Altman </PERSON>, who seems to have already gotten the only review he needs: `` I got a nice letter from <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Wouk </PERSON> who said it was the first time any of his work had ever been translated even close to his satisfaction,'' <PERSON> Altman </PERSON> said. `` I have it in my jacket.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
