<HEAD>``Timeline'' Series Seeks To Bring History Alive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEEL, ISLE OF MAN, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 History is repeating itself on the Isle of Man as <PERSON> William </PERSON> the Conqueror and his cohorts prepare once again for the Battle of <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> in 1066. Only this time <PERSON> William </PERSON> will be an actor wearing chain mail and there will be television cameras looking on, reporting the war as it happens. With an 11-week shoot on 18 European locations, `` Timeline'' is using on-camera reporters and an anchorman, all played by professional actors, to turn the distant past into the stuff of today's nightly news. `` It's a way to give history the immediacy and excitement of a fast-breaking news story,'' said <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Eaton </PERSON>, the director and executive producer. The six-hour $ 2.2 million series applies the tenets of broadcast news to over 400 years of medieval history. The show, featuring about 280 speaking parts and up to 5,000 extras, is to be aired on public television in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in January and later on <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Channel 4. `` It's dramatized but it's not drama; it's history, but it's not a history lesson,'' <PERSON> Eaton </PERSON> said in an interview before flying to the Isle of Man, a picturesque if blustery island in the Irish Sea 30 miles west of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. In the present segment, the first to be shot, it's September 25, 1066, and the Manx village of Peel, population 2,500, is standing in for the French coastal town of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valery-sur-Somme </LOCATION>. The Norman duke, <PERSON> William </PERSON>, is waiting for the winds to change so that his troops can sail across the English Channel and fight the Battle of <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> on October 14, 1066. `` Everybody's sitting about bored, ready to go,'' said production designer <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Wooley </PERSON>, as a motley group of local extras and actors rehearsed their scenes amid the ruins of a hilltop castle on the island's western coast. `` In the pivotal scene, the wind does change,'' <PERSON> Wooley </PERSON> said. `` Instead of <PERSON> William </PERSON> the Conqueror, he should have been called <PERSON> William </PERSON> the Lucky.'' The series will cover such events as the Black Death, which wiped out one-third of the world populace during the 14th and 15th centuries, and the conquest of <LOCATION> Istanbul </LOCATION>, then Constantinople, in 1453. <PERSON> Eaton </PERSON> said he avoided recent events in choosing what to dramatize. `` We first set down the parameters to cover the coming of Christianity and the Roman Empire up to the Industrial Revolution,'' said the director, an <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> graduate who began his career as a tea-boy on the set of the hit TV series `` The Avengers.'' `` Beyond that, history gets complicated; you can no longer simplify it in quite this way.'' The show's historical adviser, <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> Meisel </PERSON>, disagreed: `` A medievalist would say the further back you go, the more complicated history gets.'' She said the complications make history interesting. `` We are lulled by similarities in thinking, ` Ah yes, they -LRB- historical figures -RRB- are just like us,' but they really were n't,'' said <PERSON> Meisel </PERSON>, wrapped in a scarf and a winter coat against the coastal chill. `` The past is not like the present; that's what makes it a useful intellectual exercise.'' On sabbatical from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, where she is a professor of medieval history, <PERSON> Meisel </PERSON> said she approved of the show's efforts to make history accessible. `` I know there are some historians who really object to the idea,'' she said. `` -LRB- But -RRB- I guess my feeling is that history is so badly taught, as long as we have the football coach or the basketball coach _ whichever one is n't teaching English _ teach history, I'd like to see history that looks right and is right and entertaining.'' <PERSON> Meisel </PERSON> said her task was to verify matters ranging from historical methodology to horns. `` Did Vikings remove the horns on cattle or not?'' she said. `` We have this pseudo-Viking from a university whose particular field is agricultural animals in the Middle Ages who's saying you can not have lopped-off horns. `` But I can show you Anglo-Saxon laws where people were in fact required to lop off the horns of cattle so you do not <PERSON> gore </PERSON> your neighbors, or your neighbors' cattle.'' For locals such as blacksmith <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, `` Timeline'' is an opportunity to recreate his real-life profession on-screen. `` It's good fun; the island could do with something like this to put it on the map,'' the 42-year-old <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> said. His wife, <PERSON> Gillian </PERSON>, has a bit part in the show as well, playing what <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> described as `` a lusty maiden, or something.'' Co-producer <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Witt </PERSON> had nothing but praise for his cast: `` We're smearing mud on their costumes, and they're letting us do it. God love'em,'' he said.
</TEXT>
