<HEAD>Many in Namibia Wary of South Africa's Motives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> WINDHOEK </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ In a far-off garrison town, blacks complain of abuse and atrocities by South African soldiers based there. Here in <LOCATION> Windhoek </LOCATION> white secretaries take memos from black Cabinet members and pour their tea. Officially, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s vision of <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s future reflects the hilltop harmony of <LOCATION> Windhoek </LOCATION>, the territory's capital, rather than the garrison town, <LOCATION> Oshakati </LOCATION>, near wartorn <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> to the north. But many South-West Africans, moderates as well as militants, are deeply suspicious of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s intentions toward <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s last colony, also known as <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> These suspicions were heightened in early April when President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> came for a visit and proposed new powers for his chief representative in the territory. The proposal was seen as weakening the `` transitional'' government installed by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in 1985 to lay the groundwork for independence. Moderates who hold a majority on the coalition Cabinet accused <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> of undermining their efforts to gain credibility as an alternative to the pro-independence guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION>. `` Actions like this wo n't help force <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> to the bargaining table,'' said the Cabinet's chairman, <PERSON> Moses </PERSON> <PERSON> Katjiuongua </PERSON>, a black, who has threatened to quit. `` We're trying to get people to talk to us, but you do n't talk to people who do n't have power.'' <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, carries on in its 22-year-old bush war for independence despite heavy losses and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s overwhelming military advantage. Guerrilla leaders and many others are skeptical of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s professed willingness to allow <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nations-supervised </LOCATION> independence elections in the territory upon the withdrawal of Cuban troops helping fight a pro-Western faction in neighboring <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, which formally recognizes the name <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, has designated <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> as the `` sole and authentic'' representative of the South-West African people, atlhough more than 40 political parties operate in the territory. By all accounts, <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> would be the likely winner in a U.N.-run election because of its strong support in the Ovambo region around <LOCATION> Oshakati </LOCATION>, where about half the territory's 1.3 million people live. But widespread doubts persist that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> would agree to elections in which the Marxist-oriented <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> leaders had the edge. On at least one major issue, <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s moderates and militants share common ground. Both want an end to apartheid-style laws that create ethnically based political structures and enable the 78,000 whites to maintain segregated schools and hospitals. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, although hinting at some flexibility on the issue, has made it clear he wants to protect the `` group rights'' of whites. The president's chief representative in the territory, Administrator-General <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Pienaar </PERSON>, says whites should have the option of joining a non-racial system or maintaining a segregated administration to finance and run their own affairs. `` The whites are only 6 percent of the population, but they manage the infrastructure and the economy,'' <PERSON> Pienaar </PERSON> maintained. `` They ca n't be written off because of their small numbers.'' This attitude irks white moderates such as <PERSON> Dirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Mudge </PERSON>, the minister of finance and government affairs, who opposes ethnic politics and holds that whites do n't need discriminatory laws to preserve their culture. But conservative whites are pressing <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> to maintain some type of political apartheid, and the increasingly powerful far-right in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> is likely to create an uproar if non-racialism becomes law in the territory. `` It's discrimination that makes so many people hostile to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Katjiuongua </PERSON>, the Cabinet chairman. `` I want to be a national leader, not an ethnic leader.'' As big as <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> combined, mineral-rich <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has been administered by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> since the end of World War I, under a League of Nations mandate. In the early 1970s the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> formally declared it a territory illegally occupied by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and has called repeatedly for independence elections that would include <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION>. The new powers extended to Administrator-General <PERSON> Pienaar </PERSON> authorize him to act against news media and organizations deemed to be `` subversive,'' but for now a relatively high degree of political freedom exists. <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> is allowed to function as a political organization, and a pro-SWAPO weekly newspaper, The Namibian, regularly reports on alleged atrocities by the security forces in <LOCATION> Ovambo </LOCATION>. During <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s visit, <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> supporters demonstrated in downtown <LOCATION> Windhoek </LOCATION>, displaying placards with slogans such as `` Botha: Stop Sucking Our Blood.'' The police kept a low profile. Not everyone blames <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> for the many divisions within <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, but the widespread sentiment is that heavy-handed moves by <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s government wo n't improve the situation.
</TEXT>
