<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> moved closer to a national contract settlement after wrapping up all but final details of related agreements covering former <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> workers in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> Vice President <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said. `` It means now we can turn our full attention to the national talks. They're going very well,'' <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said Monday, adding that since last week, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> management's `` attitude has changed for the positive.''
