<HEAD>Oil Prices Slide In Reaction to OPEC News</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures prices have turned sharply lower in response to <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s failure to set temporary production cuts in four days of negotiations. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the June contract for West Texas Intermediate oil, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> benchmark crude, slid to $ 17.14 per barrel on Monday, down 85 cents from Friday's close. Most of the ground was lost early in the day as traders reacted to the news that the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> had suspended talks over proposals to cut its output in conjunction witheindependent producers. Prices stabilized temporarily in the afternoon, then slipped again in a late spurt of nervous selling. Prices for refined products also tumbled. Wholesale prices for unleaded gasoline fell 2.24 cents per gallon to 49.37 cents, while heating oil dropped 2.42 cents to 45.95 per gallon. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> ministers broke off their talks with several outside oil producers after <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> scuttled a plan for cutting production temporarily. Analysts said the suspension of the talks and the Saudis' reluctance to agree to the cuts caused a violent shift of sentiment in the futures markets, where prices had recently advanced on the expectation of a global move to reduce production
