<HEAD>NBC Agrees to Buy Cable Channel, Launch Two New Cable Services</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which operates the nation's top-rated television network, plans a major cable television venture featuring original business and sports programming. The move marks the network's biggest step yet into the cable industry, which it long has eyed as a potential way to complement its over-the-air broadcasting. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary said Monday it had signed a letter of intent to buy a cable television newtork, <ORGANIZATION> Tempo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION>, and hoped to have new business and sports programming on it later this year or early in 1989. Terms of the deal were not disclosed. `` We believe this is an important step in our efforts to broaden <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s business base,'' said <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, who for some time has been looking to get the company into cable. Tempo, which is based in <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>, and has about 12 million subscribers, is being acquired by <ORGANIZATION> Tele-Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> area-based company that is the nation's biggest cable television operator. A statement issued by <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> said that in addition to giving up its prospective interest in Tempo, <ORGANIZATION> Tele-Communications </ORGANIZATION> had agreed to offer the new programming services on its own cable systems and on affiliates that serve 8 million cable subscribers. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Malone </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Tele-Communications </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` We feel <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s proposed services will be very appealing options for the cable viewer and believe the rest of the cable industry will be enthusiastic about this opportunity.'' The announcement said <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>, Tempo and <ORGANIZATION> Tele-Communications </ORGANIZATION> hoped to sign final agreements by the end of May. In the meantime, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> said, it would discuss affilation agreements for the new programs with other cable operators. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> frequently has expressed an interest in getting the company into cable television since <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> acquired <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> in 1986. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> began talks last fall about buying a stake in <ORGANIZATION> Turner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> but those negotiations were suspended in January. More recently, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> said it had informally discussed with <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> and other cable operators the possibility of selling broadcast rights to some events in the Summer Olympics. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> owns the rights to broadcast the games. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> also recently announced it had agreed to produce a new comedy to be aired on the Disney cable channel. This would not be the first corporate link between an over-the-air broadcast network and a cable service. <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities-ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> network </ORGANIZATION>, also owns 80 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> ESPN </ORGANIZATION> cable network. Tempo Television provides programming aimed mainly at viewers over age 45 in four categories _ entertainment, travel, sports-outdoors and how-to information. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s plans call for it to replace that programming with business and financial news on weekdays and sports programming in the evening and on weekends, according to spokesman <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Rutledge </PERSON>. The business news and financial information service would present consumer-oriented features and information dealing with the market, business trends and the economy, the announcement said. The sports-programming service would include live and taped coverage of sports events, interviews with sports figures, sports-oriented talk shows and magazine-format sports shows. Both services would rely on existing <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> operations, but would be distinct from <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> network programming, <PERSON> Rutledge </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said the venture `` promises to strengthen <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>, thereby preserving our long-term ability to provide first-class programming to our over-the-air broadcast audience.''
