<HEAD>USG Offers Recap As Alternative to Desert Partners Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> would take on $ 2.2 billion in new debt under a defensive recapitalization and business restructuring plan it has proposed to counter an unwanted $ 2.32 billion buyout offer by the investment group <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> L.P </ORGANIZATION>. Under its plan, USG would borrow $ 2.2 billion to pay its shareholders $ 37 in cash, debentures with a face value of $ 5 and a share of stock in the recapitalized corporation for each of their 51.5 million common shares, company officials said Monday. USG, a Chicago-based manufacturer of building products, also said it would raise money to pay off the debt by selling its <ORGANIZATION> Masonite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Kinkead </PERSON> businesses and focusing operations on its core building products businesses. The plan will be submitted June 24 to a vote of shareholders, who also will be asked to rollover certain <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION> shares held in company employee benefit plans into new shares of common stock, the company said. As expected, <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION>' reaction was negative. `` From what we have seen, <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION>'s proposal appears to be highly conditional and does not have financing in place. We note that USG proposes to move shares into an employee plan,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION>' spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Davies </PERSON>. `` It's not clear, however, what are the implications of that move with respect to control of the company. We believe that the <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION> shareholders might prefer contrary to <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION>'s recap, our fully financed $ 45 per share proposal,'' <PERSON> Davies </PERSON> said in a telephone interview Monday night. Earlier Monday, <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> had tried to lure USG to the bargaining table by offering to increase its bid for the Chicago-based manufacturer to $ 2.32 billion if the two sides can reach a friendly deal. <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION>, a partnership headed by two <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> oilmen, said in a statement that it was willing to pay $ 45 for each of 39 million USG shares if the <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION>'s management agreed to support the offer. The remaining 12.5 million shares would be acquired for subordinated discount debentures carrying a market value of $ 45 each, giving the deal a total value of about $ 2.32 billion. The partnership, led by oilmen <PERSON> Cyril </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, previously offered $ 42 a share in a hostile tender offer. That bid, including debt securities and warrants valued at $ 42 each, has a value of about $ 2.2 billion and remains in effect. <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> owns about 9.9 percent of <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION>'s shares and said that as of Friday, about 19.3 million shares, or 37.5 percent, had been tendered under its $ 42-a-share offer. Analysts said that <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION>' latest proposal was rather conservative and that a bid of $ 50 a share would far more attractive to USG, a manufacturer of paper, plaster and wood products. In takeover overtures last year, <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> indicated it was willing to pay $ 50 a share for the company. On composite trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION> rose 50 cents to close at $ 41.50 a share Monday. In proposing a friendly resolution, <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION>' chief financial officer, <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>, said that `` all aspects of our proposal, including price, are negotiable.'' Among the big bargaining chips <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION> executives control is the company's `` poison-pill'' defense, which is designed to hinder an unwanted takeover. Last week a federal judge in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> denied a request from <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> to prevent USG from using the defense measure. <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> said it intended to appeal the ruling. `` The poison pill is a way for management to negotiate,'' said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Horan </PERSON>, a vice president at the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` What -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- is trying to do is get USG management to negotiate, not to sit there and say the company's not up for sale,'' he added. The standoff appears headed for a showdown at <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION>'s annual meeting May 11. Desert Partners has nominated a slate of six candidates to <ORGANIZATION> USG </ORGANIZATION>'s 15-member board. `` We believe the stockholders will demonstrate their support of good-faith negotiations by voting for the <ORGANIZATION> Desert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> director candidates,'' <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> said.
