<HEAD>First National Bank Sued for Pension Plan Bias</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal government has filed a lawsuit against <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>, charging the bank with discriminating against men and women through various features of its pension plan. The lawsuit, filed Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> Equal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opportunity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, asks that <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> change its pension plans and pay monetary damages to employees. No specific damages were mentioned in the lawsuit, but <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON> said the amount would be `` very substantial.'' The lawsuit involves one claim of discrimination against men and two against women. The claim of discrimination against men is based on a provision in the pension plans that calculates pension amounts for each employee at retirement using a percentage of that person's earnings. <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON> said the men are credited with a lower percentage than women for employment before 1965. The commission claims that the bank in 1970, in an effort to correct the problem, lowered women's pension benefits to be equal to those of men, a move the <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> says is illegal. A third claim involves the use of sex-based mortality tables for calculating pension benefits. The commission said such tables result in lower monthly benefits for women because women retirees on average live longer than men. <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON> said the bank stopped using the sex-based mortality tables about four years ago but did n't change its practices for prior periods of employment.
</TEXT>
