<HEAD>China to Start Futures Markets This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> plans to open up to five futures markets in the southern city of <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION> later this year, becoming the first socialist country to take such a step, according to a report published Tuesday. The English-language <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> quoted unnamed sources as saying preparations were under way to set up three to five pilot markets in <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION>, one of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s most important business centers. Chinese leaders hope the markets will stabilize the economy and prevent drastic price increases that have become a main complaint of Chinese citizens, the newspaper said. A futures market allows traders and producers to negotiate a set price for what they think a commodity will be worth at a future date. The producer is guaranteed that price regardless of subsequent fluctuations in the market. The report said officials from the cities of <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wuhan </LOCATION> and the provinces of <LOCATION> Guangdong </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Henan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jilin </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Hunan </PERSON> met in mid-April to discuss plans for the futures markets, but did not say what commodities would be traded. This is the latest development in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s decade-long economic reform that has increasingly turned to capitalistic practices in its attempt to strengthen and enliven the economy. The official Economic Daily earlier this year described how a futures market would solve the problem of gluts and shortages, which often are the result of farmers' inability to forecast the market. Both papers acknowledged that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s backward communications and transport systems will be a problem, but the <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> said, `` ... The country can not wait until everything is ready before carrying out the plans.'' The paper said <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> leaders want to learn from the experience of foreign countries in futures markets and that experts from <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> will be consulted. It said no decision has been made yet on whether foreigners will be allowed to trade in the markets.
