<FIRST>a f BC-LatinDebtSwaps Adv07-08   05-03 0979</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Latin Debt Swaps, Adv 07-08,1003</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 07</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions May 7-8 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Equity Swaps Possible Way to Reduce Huge Latin Debt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto RIO1 of May 2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE HANDLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It looked like the movie `` Wall Street.'' Brokers wearing yellow `` yuppie'' ties, waving I.D. tags and shouting into walkie-talkies, jostled one another to make bids on the floor of the <ORGANIZATION> Rio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. But the object of the bidding was not stocks, bonds, commodities or precious metals. It was part of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s mountainous foreign debt of $ 121 billion. Thoughout <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, which as a whole owes the rest of the world $ 410 billion and has been unable to pay it back, so-called `` debt-for-equity swaps'' are being tried as a way to break the impasse. Not everyone is enthusiastic about the idea, which involves trading big debts for generally smaller amounts of equity in local enterprises. Some countries say the swaps cause inflation and lead to `` foreign domination'' of their economies. Some major creditor banks, mostly <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ones, which sank billions into Latin loans, say the swaps force them to cancel their debt at too hefty a discount. On the other hand, many small banks _ in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> cities such as <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> _ see the swaps as a way to salvage at least some of the money they sunk into the region in the 1970s. `` Swaps will never be a total solution to the debt crisis. But they certainly are a step in the right direction,'' said <PERSON> Maarten </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pronk </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> representative of <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> NMB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, currently the world's No. 1 middleman in debt-for-equity trades. `` There are pluses and minuses on both sides, but the overall result is very interesting.'' In <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, which has just begun monthly debt auctions, equity trades could reduce the country's foreign debt by as much as $ 4 billion this year, officials estimate. In a typical transaction, a company hoping to start or expand a Brazilian business purchases a certain amount of the country's debt from a creditor bankat a steep discount and then brings that debt to market to bid against other companies on a repayment plan from the central bank of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. Successful bidders _ the ones who accept the biggest discounts from the central bank _ get repaid in local currency, which is to be invested in their local enterprises. The benefit to the companies comes in the difference between what they paid for the debt and what the central bank agrees to repay them. For example, a company might purchase debt at 50 cents on the dollar and then win a bid of 70 cents on the dollar from the central bank in the auction. The government regulates the auctions, screens the types of projects to be funded and sets quotas on the amount of debt it will repay. While the process helps ease the national debt burden, the regulations are designed to control the inflationary effects of the swaps, which infuse the economy with fresh capital and increase the money in circulation. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, like most other countries, also protects its end of the deal by requiring investors to keep their assets in the country for a period of years. `` The Rio debt auction was a complete success,'' <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barcellos </PERSON>, the president of the <ORGANIZATION> Rio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> exchange </ORGANIZATION>, said in an interview. Another aggressive debt swapper is <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, which still owes an estimated $ 21.7 billion but has traded off $ 3 billion worth. Thanks to such deals, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, Australian, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> private interests have bought into Chilean mining companies, private pension funds, fruit-growing firms and fishing companies. Some critics complain that encouraging foreign interests to swap debt for equity could lead to a `` denationalization'' of the Latin American economy. But in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, the authoritarian regime of President Gen. <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> says the swaps will continue, especially since the country is writing off debt at the rate of 59 to 61 cents on the dollar. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, the No. 2 Third World debtor owing $ 105 billion, swapped some $ 2 billion of debt for local assets but stopped the program last year when the inflation rate hit a record 159.2 percent. Under the Mexican swaps, made at a discount of around 30 percent, <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Med </ORGANIZATION> acquired or increased holdings in the country. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, third among Latin debtors with $ 55 billion owed, this year held two debt-for-equity auctions and authorized 15 specific debt-swap deals. In these projects, $ 241 million worth of debt is to be canceled in exchange for $ 139 million worth of ownership in two breweries, a soft drink bottling plant, a beer bottling company, an auto parts firm and a manufacturer of insulin. But <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ciminari </PERSON>, the secretary of industry and foreign trade, echoed <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s worries about inflation. With <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s inflation rate running over 200 percent a year, the swap program could get tripped up, he said. Small, poor <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> has succeeded in reducing its $ 900 million debt to foreign banks by swapping part of it for local assets _ at the bargain-basement rate of 11 cents on the dollar. But there is controversy, because of fear foreigners will gain control of traditionally state-run companies. <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> has gone timidly into debt swaps. <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> says it intends to start them. <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION> have n't shown much interest in such operations, while <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, which has openly refused to repay most of its $ 16.7 billion debt, does n't consider swaps at all. Also generally in the anti-swap camp are the giant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks that tied up billions of dollars in Latin American loans. <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Chase </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guaranty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> are, in principle, against huge discounts on the money owed to them.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions May 7-8</NOTE>
