 Stock prices advanced in moderate activity today, supported by heavy dividend trading and a firmer bond market. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 8.79 to 2,052.06 by noon on Wall Street. Advancers outnumbered decliners by roughly 3 to 2 in the overall tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 763 issues higher, 529 lower and 523 unchanged. <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> volume totaled 101.66 million shares at mid-day. Much of the session's early activity centered on heavy trading in <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION>, which goes ex-dividend today. The stock led the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>'s most-active list, rising \ to 27 -RRB-. `` Without that, volume would be extraordinarily low,'' noted <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Metz </PERSON>, vice president and technical analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Oppenheimer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Trading volume also was sluggish because of a delay the opening of the futures pits in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, where the futures on the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION>'s 500 index are traded The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> halted activity for more than two and a half hours after a water main flooded the basement and disrupted telephone contact with the outside world. `` That's kept all the program trading out of the market,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Vandenberg </PERSON>, a trader at <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` All the people who read off the spread between index futures and t