<HEAD>State Oil Regulator Wants To Keep OPEC Contacts Open</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Hance </PERSON>, one of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>' three oil regulators, says the state benefited from his attendance at last week's <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> meeting, and he plans to keep those contacts open despite the criticism the trip drew. `` We're not trying to join <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>, and we're not always going to agree with them,'' said <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Hance </PERSON>, who sits on the three-member <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. `` But when President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> tried to get nuclear arms stability, he had to deal with the <LOCATION> Russians </LOCATION>, who are our enemies.'' <PERSON> Hance </PERSON> did not participate in meetings held by the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION>, but rather visited with some individual oil ministers during his stay in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. `` The critical thing is _ we're living in a world where someone else sets the price for our commodity. We have to have input,'' he said in an interview Monday. Not everyone agreed. One group called Monday for <PERSON> Hance </PERSON> to be prosecuted on charges of violating the Logan Act, which bans private citizens from interfering with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign policy. The <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION>, which says it has 12 million members who favor low energy prices, wrote <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> urging that he prosecute <PERSON> Hance </PERSON>. `` It would appear that Commissioner <PERSON> Hance </PERSON>'s efforts to assist <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> in fixing world oil prices are in direct opposition to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign and economic policy,'' the letter said. `` Commissioner <PERSON> Hance </PERSON> is carrying on a blatant campaign to assist <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> in raising world oil prices and damaging <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic interests.'' The <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> meeting ended Monday with no agreement on a proposed 2 percent cut in the group's oil production, a move aimed at stabilizing prices that have undergone big fluctuations since late 1985. The proposal was made after six non-OPEC oil countries offered to reduce their production if <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> made a similar cut. `` I am disappointed that ... they did not reach an agreement.'' <PERSON> Hance </PERSON> said. `` I figured that if they did n't, prices would slide a little temporarily and then they would come back.'' Despite the meeting's breakdown, however, <PERSON> Hance </PERSON> said he agreed with predictions that world oil prices would stabilize near recent levels. In fact, prices did take a hard fall amid market disappointment at the meeting's failure _ but not low enough to match levels that existed before the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> session was called early last month. At the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, for example, <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, fell 85 cents a barrel to $ 17.14 Monday. In early April, it had traded in high $ 16 range. For 40 years, the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> helped set world oil prices. The commission has monitored oil output since an oil price crash in the 1930s, and under state law the agency has authority to restrict production to avoid waste and to protect reserves. <PERSON> Hance </PERSON> made no apologies for his trip, which also drew criticism from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. He said <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> officials should attend the next <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> session in June because `` what happens in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> meetings will have more impact on our economy than anything that will happen in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> or in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Hance </PERSON> invited <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s president, plus oil officials from several other nations, to visit <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and learn more about the <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'s production monitoring system. `` <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> is coming Wednesday,'' he said, adding that <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s president or his representative likely would visit the state this summer
