<SECOND>AM-Merc Trading Halt, Bjt,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sprinkler System Mishap Forces Trading Halt At Merc</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Trading halted for more than 2 -LCB- hours Tuesday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> after water from a burst pipe flooded the exchange's telecommunications room, disabling its automated price quotation system. The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> is the leading <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market for stock-index and livestock futures, and the trading shutdown had a quieting effect on the nation's other financial markets, analysts said. `` We do n't know what caused it but it leaked a whole lot of water,'' exchange spokesman <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Yemma </PERSON> said after trading resumed at 10:45 a.m. CDT. Exchange officials called the trading halt at 8:05 a.m. CDT., 45 minutes after the opening of trading in foreign currency and <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bill futures Trading in stock-index and agricultural futures had not yet opened when the halt was called, <PERSON> Yemma </PERSON> said. A large water pipe in the sprinkler system burst and flooded the second-floor telecommunications room, located just below the exchange's trading floor, he said. The water disabled the exchange's high-speed telephone lines, which carry price quotes to subscribers of market-information services around the world. The exchange's computers were not damaged, so trading could have continued but `` the customers and users of the market would n't have known what the prices were,'' <PERSON> Yemma </PERSON> said. During the trading halt, stock market players were unable to hedge their equity investments via the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s popular <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 futures contract. That may have limited trading activity on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, analysts said. `` You're definitely not going to see anybody make a big play without the futures open,'' said <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Liming </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> LNS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. While the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> was down, he said, `` There was one or two things less to watch on what was a quiet day to begin with.'' <PERSON> Yemma </PERSON> said it was impossible to calculate the dollar value of the loss of volume at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> MidAmerica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, which trades smaller versions of the most popular futures contracts offered by other exchanges, may have benefited from the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION>'s problems, however. Spokesman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Murschel </PERSON> said the MidAm halted trading in its stock-index, livestock, foreign currency and <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bill futures at the same time as the <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, then resumed trading in those contracts at 10 a.m. CDT when it appeared the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> might be closed for a day or more. `` When the MidAm reopened, it really became the marketplace for those contracts that were affected by the <ORGANIZATION> CME </ORGANIZATION>, so there was an alternative marketplace available,'' <PERSON> Murschel </PERSON> said. `` It was the MidAm's day in the sun.''
