<HEAD>U.S. Presses For South Korea To Remove Import Barriers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> Tuesday asked <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to protect American intellectual property rights and lift sales restrictions on foreign cigarettes, government officials said. In the second day of a scheduled three-day trade meeting which opened in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> on Monday, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> also asked <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to open its advertising and insurance markets, the officials said. `` The meeting was very useful. There were detailed discussions on almost all pending issues,'' a South Korean official said after Tuesday's talks. The 19-member <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegation, headed by <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Allgier </PERSON>, assistant chief of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, demanded that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> protect 911 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> chemical products which are patented but not marketed, retroactive to Jan. 1, 1987, the officials said. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> promised to reply to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> request before the <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> meeting ends on Wednesday, they said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials also called for the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> government to tighten control on pirated books under a 1985 agreement, in which <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> officials promised to protect the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> copyrights, the officials said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> took a critical stand on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s cigarette sales system and demanded that the prices of imported foreign cigarettes be lowered to the level of domestic brands, they said Imported American cigarettes sell for $ 1.76 a pack compared with 81 cents a pack for the most expensive local brand. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> also asked <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to permit cigarette advertisements through all news media, but <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> said the advertisements would be limited to magazines, the officials said.
