<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0200</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market advanced today, but most of its gains were concentrated in blue-chip takeover targets and in dividend-related trading. Analysts said that aside from pockets of activity, trading was a bit lackluster. But they noted the market's improvement was more apparent than in previous weeks. Much of the session's activity centered on heavy trading in <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION>, which goes ex-dividend today. Takeover stocks also helped drive the market higher. Analysts said these issues heated up in anticipation that cash will soon be freed up as a handful of other takeover deals come to a close. Program traders were shut out of the market in the early going because of a water main break at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where the futures on the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 index are traded. Activity was halted for more than two and a half hours. Some analysts welcomed the respite. On Wall Street, `` it's a refreshing case of a stock market rather than a casino,'' <PERSON> Metz </PERSON> said. Arbitragers remained mostly on the sidelines once futures activity resumed, analysts said.
