<HEAD>Kodak Reports $260 Million in Quarterly Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s earnings rose 46 percent in the first quarter of 1988, to $ 260 million from $ 178 million a year ago, the company said Tuesday. The photographic giant said the increase was due to increases in sales volume, the weak dollar, and earnings from <ORGANIZATION> Sterling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> acquired in February. On a per share basis, <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> earned 80 cents in the first three months of the year, compared to 53 cents during the first quarter of 1987. Sales increased 25 percent to $ 3.33 billion from $ 2.65 billion last year. Analysts said the results were better than expected. The only surprise in the report was a 2 percent earnings drop in the company's imaging segment, which includes photography and copiers, according to <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, of <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said the decline was due to repackaging of certain film products and increased advertising expenses. He said, however, the expenditures would pay off later. Another analyst, <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Glazer </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said a large portion of the per share earnings increase, 27 cents, was due to the declining value of the dollar, which makes foreign profits worth more in dollar terms. <PERSON> Glazer </PERSON> said it was a `` low quality source'' of earnings gain. He said the sale of assets in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> resulted in another 4 cents of the per-share gain. Both analysts noted strong gains in the company's chemicals segment and the Sterling Drug subsidiary. Sales rose in each of <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>'s three segments. Sales in its imaging segment were $ 2 billion, up from $ 1.8 billion last year. Chemical sales were $ 654 million, up from $ 588 million. And sales in health products were $ 640 million, up from $ 274 million. Sales outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> were healthy _ up 23 percent in the imaging segment, up 16 percent in chemicals, and up 104 percent in health.
