<HEAD>Staley Rejects British Firm's Sweetened Buyout Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROLLING MEADOWS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Staley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> announced Tuesday its board rejected a sweetened $ 1.42 billion takeover bid from British sugar producer <ORGANIZATION> Tate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Lyle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> and may consider other offers. <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> Chairman <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nordlund </PERSON> said several unidentified `` third parties'' are interested in acquiring the company, based in this northwest <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> suburb. `` The company is continuing discussions with certain third parties and expects to enter into negotiations,'' <PERSON> Nordlund </PERSON> said in a statement issued by the company. In <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading Tuesday, <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> shares advanced 50 cents to $ 38.375. <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>'s board recommended that the company's stockholders reject the $ 35-a-share bid, which was made last week and approved Tuesday by <ORGANIZATION> Tate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> shareholders meeting in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. When it first moved to take over <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> last month, the British company offered $ 32 per share of common stock. <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' second-larged refiner of corn sweeteners behind Decatur-based <ORGANIZATION> Archer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daniels </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, urged its stockholders April 21 to reject the first offer. In its statement Tuesday, <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> said its financial advisers _ <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Markets </ORGANIZATION> _ had concluded the revised <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> offer was `` inadequate.'' <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>'s board did not make a recommendation on <PERSON> Tate </PERSON>'s offers of $ 53.15 a share for depositary preferred stock or $ 105 a share for cumulative preference stock. But the company's statement noted the British company's takeover bid was conditioned on receiving a minimum number of common-stock shares and that <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>'s board has recommended rejecting the common stock bid. In a related matter, <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>'s board extended its `` poison pill'' anti-takeover defense until May 10 at 5 p.m. Tate's revised bid expires at midnight -LRB- EDT -RRB- on that date. Spokesmen for the companies did not return telephone messages Tuesday seeking comment. But industry analysts have said <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> has a fair market value of about $ 40 a share. After <PERSON> Tate </PERSON>'s first offer, <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayer </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said that if he were a <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> stockholder, he probably would n't sell for less than $ 40. <ORGANIZATION> Tate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> owns about 5 percent of <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>'s stock and wants to acquire the entire company for its A.E. <ORGANIZATION> Staley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, which produces corn sweeteners. <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> was based in <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, until about three years ago when it moved its headquarters to <ORGANIZATION> Rolling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Meadows </ORGANIZATION>. The British company has promised to move <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>'s headquarters back to the central <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> city if its takeover succeeds. <ORGANIZATION> Staley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> also owns <ORGANIZATION> CFS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a leading food-service supplier.
