<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Future airline competition will revolve more around service than price, the chief executive of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> says. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON>, who also has headed <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Tiger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and the former <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, told a group of business editors and writers Tuesday that `` service will be the prime determinant of how well any airline competes in the future.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market gained ground Tuesday, as the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 15.09 to 2,058.36. Bond prices rose modestly in light trading. The dollar rose narrowly on domestic markets but fell overseas in foreign exchange trading. Gold futures prices dipped to their lowest levels in more than six weeks, but energy futures rallied, cattle futures rose and grains and soybeans fell.
