<HEAD>Eastern Seeks Clarification of Order Barring Shuttle Sale</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS new grafs 2-6 with new FAA probe, edits throughout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> has asked a federal judge to clarify his order barring the financially troubled carrier from selling its Northeast shuttle service to another subsidiary of its parent, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. Meanwhile, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> is investigating Machinist union charges that the Miami-based carrier is guessing the weight of cargo aboard its aircraft. `` We've been looking into the allegations for about a week and a half,'' <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` We have not found any irregularities yet.'' The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> has already fined <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> $ 823,500 for safety violations and is conducting an inspection of its fleet. Eastern spokesman <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said the airline `` is absolutely safe in all phases of its operations'' and accused the Machinists of using safety issues as a smokescreen to obscure economic issues in contract negotiations. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the motion by <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, which was filed last week under seal in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, appears to have been made in an attempt to ensure that a planned business transaction would not violate a series of orders issued by District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON>. In March, <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON> held <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> in contempt of a July 2, 1987, order issued in a labor dispute for taking steps to sell the <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shuttle </ORGANIZATION> to a newly created subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 225 million. The service operates between <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON> barred Eastern from taking any further steps to sell the shuttle, ruling the transaction would violate the status quo in working conditions he had ordered last summer. The proposed sale was opposed by the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union, which charged the company was trying to undermine the union's ability to represent shuttle employees by transferring the operation to another subsidiary. <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> refused to comment Tuesday on why the airlines filed the motion, saying only: `` The entire letter is under seal and we do not care to clarify.'' Court documents requesting that the clarification motion be placed under seal said Eastern was trying to protect `` confidential and proprietary information about its business plans.'' `` Eastern would be placed at a serious and irreparable competitive disadvantage if the information contained in the motion and memorandum and supporting affidavits is made public,'' the company's deputy general counsel, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, said in a sworn affidavit. `` Disclosure of the information could impair <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s ability to manage its operations and to resolve its financial difficulties.'' In a reply to <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s request, attorneys for the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> said the union did not agree with the airline's interpretation of <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON>'s order. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> here is scheduled to hear arguments Thursday on <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s appeal of <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON>'s order barring the shuttle sale.
